# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 2, 1828.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Just as in the 1824 election, President John Quincy Adams of the National Republican Party faced Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party, making the election the second rematch in presidential history.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties were new organizations, and this was the first presidential election their nominees contested.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the collapse of the Federalist Party, four members of the Democratic-Republican Party, including Jackson and Adams, had sought the presidency in the 1824 election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had won a plurality (but not majority) of both the electoral vote and popular vote in the 1824 election, but had lost the contingent election that was held in the House of Representatives.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the aftermath of the election, Jackson's supporters accused Adams and Henry Clay of having reached a "corrupt bargain" in which Clay helped Adams win the contingent election in return for the position of Secretary of State.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the 1824 election, Jackson's supporters immediately began plans for a campaign in 1828, and the Democratic-Republican Party fractured into the National Republican Party and the Democratic Party during Adams's presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The 1828 campaign was marked by large amounts of "mudslinging", as both parties attacked the personal qualities of the opposing party's candidate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson dominated in the South and the West, aided in part by the passage of the Tariff of 1828.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the ongoing expansion of the right to vote to most white men, the election marked a dramatic expansion of the electorate, with 9.5% of Americans casting a vote for president, compared with 3.4% in 1824.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Several states transitioned to a popular vote for president, leaving South Carolina and Delaware as the only states in which the legislature chose presidential electors.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson decisively won the election, carrying 55.5% of the popular vote and 178 electoral votes, to Adams' 83.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the rise of Jacksonian Democracy and the transition from the First Party System to the Second Party System.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historians debate the significance of the election, with many arguing that it marked the beginning of modern American politics by removing key barriers to voter participation and establishing a stable two-party system.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson became the first president whose home state was neither Massachusetts nor Virginia, while Adams was the second to lose re-election, following his father John Adams.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, unsuccessful candidate and Speaker of the House at the time, despised Jackson, in part due to their fight for Western votes during the election, and he chose to support Adams, which led to Adams being elected president on the first ballot.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A few days after the election, Adams appointed Clay his Secretary of State, a position held by Adams and his three immediate predecessors prior to becoming president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson and his followers promptly accused Clay and Adams of striking a "corrupt bargain," and continued to lambaste the president until the 1828 election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In 1824, the national Democratic-Republican Party collapsed as national politics became increasingly polarized between supporters of Adams and supporters of Jackson.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In a prelude to the presidential election, the Jacksonians bolstered their numbers in Congress in the 1826 congressional elections, with Jackson ally Andrew Stevenson chosen as the new Speaker of the House of Representatives in 1827 over Adams ally Speaker, John W.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In October 1825, the Tennessee legislature re-nominated Jackson for president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional opponents of Adams, including former William H.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford supporter Martin Van Buren, rallied around Jackson's candidacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's supporters called themselves *Democrats*, and would formally organize as the Democratic Party shortly after his election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In hopes of uniting those opposed to Adams, Jackson ran on a ticket with Calhoun.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] No congressional nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' relationship with Vice President John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun deteriorated, with Calhoun opposing Clay's appointment as Secretary of State due to his own presidential ambitions.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1826, Calhoun gave his support to Jackson for the 1828 election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun's stance on the removal of Native Americans was not accepted by the Georgian electors who instead voted for William Smith.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, who supported Crawford during the 1824 election, supported Jackson during the 1828 election and aided in the selection of Calhoun as vice president in order to prevent DeWitt Clinton, his political enemy, from being selected.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren arranged for incidents to divide Calhoun and Adams such as him abstaining from a vote on tariff legislation supported by Adams in order for Calhoun to break the tie by voting against it.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Ritchie, editor of the *Richmond Examiner*, was one of the leading supporters of Crawford during the 1824 election and Van Buren convinced him to support Jackson.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren convinced him of an alliance "between the planters of the South and the plain Republicans of the North".
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was re-nominated on the endorsement of state legislatures and partisan rallies.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] As with the Democrats, no nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams chose Secretary of the Treasury Richard Rush, a Pennsylvanian known for his protectionist views, as his running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, who was personally popular in New England, hoped to assemble a coalition in which Clay attracted Western voters, Rush attracted voters in the middle states, and Webster won over former members of the Federalist Party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams support in New York aligned with the Anti-Masonic Party and Thurlow Weed, his campaign manager in the state, was sympathetic to the anti-masonic movement.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was marked by large amounts of nasty "mudslinging." Jackson's marriage, for example, came in for the vicious attack.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Hammond, in his *Cincinnati Gazette*, asked: "Ought a convicted adulteress and her paramour husband be placed in the highest offices of this free and Christian land?" At the time of the election, Mr. and Mrs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had been happily, legally married for almost 35 years, but when they met, Rachel had been legally married to Lewis Robards.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the Adams campaign managers' hands, this became a scandal.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Decades later, their youthful love story became a political liability.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson believed that attacks on him were personal vendettas consequent to past disputes, writing, "I am branded with every crime, and Doctor McNary, Col.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Erwin, Anderson and Williams are associated for this purpose." One thing that all these men had in common is that they had all known and/or been business partners and/or been military comrades of Jackson going back decades.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's campaigners fired back by claiming that while serving as minister to Russia, Adams had procured a young girl to serve as a prostitute for Emperor Alexander I.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They also stated that Adams had a billiard table in the White House and that he had charged the government for it.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (In fact Adams while minister to Russia had employed a young girl as a maid to his wife; the girl had written a letter which had been intercepted by the Russian postal services.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander I had been curious to meet the letter writer publicly at court and Adams had done so.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The billiard table was Adams' personal property; a bill for repairing it had been accidentally included in the White House expense accounts.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams also came under attack for having a chess set).
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson also came under heavy attack as a slave trader who bought and sold slaves and moved them about in defiance of modern standards of morality (he was not attacked for merely owning slaves used in plantation work).
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Coffin Handbills attacked Jackson for his courts-martial, execution of deserters, and massacres of Indian villages, and also his habit of dueling and that he supposedly fought over 100 duels.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, Jackson had only fought three duels: in the first both men had fired at each other but made up; in the second duel, Jackson vs John Sevier, it had taken place but only two persons not connected with either party had been slightly injured.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The third duel was with Charles Dickinson in which Dickinson was mortally wounded while Jackson was left with a bullet in his chest.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A so-called fourth duel between Jackson and Thomas Hart Benton was in fact a frontier brawl which left Jackson badly wounded in the shoulder.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] That said the list of violent incidents involving Andrew Jackson began with his arrival in Tennessee in the 1780s and continued apace for years.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Ezra Stiles Ely attacked Adams' Unitarian beliefs and called for Christians to vote for Jackson.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson avoided articulating issue positions, instead campaigning on his personal qualities and his opposition to Adams.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams avoided popular campaigning, instead emphasizing his support of specific issues.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's praise of internal improvements in Europe, such as "lighthouses of the skies" (observatories), in his first annual message to Congress, and his suggestion that Congress not be "palsied by the will of our constituents" were given attention in and out of the press.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] People kissed babies, had picnics, and started many other traditions during the campaign.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson wrote of the outcome of the contingent election of 1825 in a letter to William H.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the next election, Jackson's and Adams's supporters saw value in establishing the opinion of Jefferson in regards to their respective candidates and against their opposition.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson died on July 4, 1826, on the same day as his predecessor, John Adams, Adams's father.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Webster recorded that Jefferson told him in December 1824 that Jackson was a dangerous man unfit for the presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Sean Wilentz described Webster's account of the meeting as "not wholly reliable." Biographer Robert V.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Gilmer accused Coles of misrepresentation, in Jefferson's opinion had changed, Gilmer said.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's son-in-law, former Virginia Governor Thomas Mann Randolph Jr., said in 1826 that Jefferson had a "strong repugnance" to Henry Clay.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Others said the same thing, but Coles could not believe Jefferson's opinion had changed.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles released a letter from Jefferson meant to be kept private to Thomas Ritchie's *Richmond Enquirer*.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was written after Adams's first annual message to Congress and it contained an attack from Jefferson on the incumbent administration.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles omitted a prior letter of Jefferson's praise of Adams for his role in the embargo of 1808.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson Randolph soon collected and published Jefferson's correspondence.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] 22.2% of the voting age population and 57.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] All of the states, except for Delaware and South Carolina, selected their electors through a popular vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The selection of electors began on October 31 with elections in Ohio and Pennsylvania and ended on November 13 with elections in North Carolina.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College met on December 3.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won the same states that his father had won in the election of 1800 (the New England states, New Jersey, and Delaware) and Maryland, but Jackson won all other states and won the election in a landslide.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party in Georgia was hopelessly divided into two factions (Troup and Clark) at the time.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, both factions nominated Jackson for President, with the election being primarily a test of the strength of these two factions - the Adams electors ran a very poor third, with just 3.21% of the vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The winning slate, which received a 3,000 vote majority.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson received 50.3% of the vote in states without slavery while he received 72.6% of the vote in states with slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] He received 200,000 votes in the South and 400,000 votes in the North, but the Three-fifths Compromise, which inflated the South's electoral votes, resulted in him receiving 105 electoral votes from the South and 73 votes from the North.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election in American history in which the incumbent president lost re-election despite winning a greater share of the popular vote than in the previous election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' loss was also the second time an elected president lost the popular vote twice, this also occurred with Benjamin Harrison in 1888 and 1892, and Donald Trump who lost the popular vote in 2016 and 2020.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which the Democrats won Kentucky until 1856.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the only election where Maine, New Hampshire, New Jersey, and Vermont voted for the National Republicans, and the last time that New Hampshire voted against the Democrats until 1856.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election in which an electoral vote split occurred in Maine until the election of 2016, the first election in which the winning ticket did not have a north–south balance, and the first election in which two northerners ran against two southerners.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (b) *Votes cast for Jackson electors nominated by the Clark faction of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two tickets pledged to Jackson ran in this state; the Clark ticket was defeated by electors nominated by the Troup faction.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] There were two Jackson tickets in Georgia representing different factions of the party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Troup faction "won" with 9,712 votes and the Clarke faction lost with 7,991.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They are combined here, though legally this is incorrect.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The state rejected returns from 10 counties and 8 others submitted none.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Including the rejected returns, the total votes are Jackson (Troup) 10,508, Jackson (Clarke) 8,854 and Adams, 642.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In Maryland's 3rd and 4th districts, voters voted for two electors, with each pledged to one candidate or another.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The votes in the 3rd were 6,177 for William Fitzhugh Jr. and 6,164 for William Tyler, both for Jackson, versus 6,117 for George Baltzell and William Price for Adams.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the 4th the votes were 6,058 for Benjamin Chew Howard and James Sewell for Jackson versus 5,743 and 5,742 for the Adams electors.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Note: Dubin mistakenly swapped the 3rd and 4th districts in his book, but that has been corrected here.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two statewide electors were chosen by the electors elected at the district level.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Rachel Jackson had been having chest pains throughout the campaign, and she was traumatized by the personal attacks on her marriage.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] She became ill and died on December 22, 1828.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson accused the Adams campaign, and Henry Clay even more so, of causing her death, saying, "I can and do forgive all my enemies.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson was sworn in as president on March 4, 1829.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the inauguration, a mob entered the White House to shake the new president's hand, damaging the furniture and lights.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson escaped through the back, and large punch bowls were set up to lure the crowd outside.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Conservatives were horrified at this event, and held it up as a portent of terrible things to come from the first Democratic president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] When Jackson arrived in Washington, D.C., he was to pay the customary courtesy call on the outgoing president, but he refused to do so.
[src:andrew-johnson/1828-united-states-presidential-election] John Quincy Adams responded by refusing to go to the inauguration of Andrew Jackson, similar to his father who did not attend the inauguration of Thomas Jefferson 28 years before.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The **1832 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 21 to May 23, 1832, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the first presidential nominating convention ever held by the Democratic Party, incumbent President Andrew Jackson was nominated for a second term, while former Secretary of State Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Anti-Masonic Party and the National Republican Party had held the first presidential nominating conventions in 1831, and Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet" helped organize a Democratic convention in 1832.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] As the party leaders assumed that Jackson would be nominated for president, the primary purpose of the convention was to find a new running mate: Vice President John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun had fallen out with Jackson following the Petticoat affair and the Nullification Crisis, and subsequently resigned the office in order to take a Senate seat.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which was presided over by Governor Robert Lucas, hosted delegates from every state except Missouri; Jackson won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] With Jackson's strong endorsement, Van Buren easily won the vice presidential nomination on the first ballot, defeating former Representative Philip P.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barbour of Virginia and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Jackson and Van Buren went on to win the 1832 presidential election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the summer of 1822, "Richmond Junto" leader Thomas Ritchie of Virginia began raising the idea of a national convention to resolve the issue of nomination; ultimately, the congressional nominating caucus was appealed to by the devotees of Treasury Secretary William H.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Following that defeat in the election of 1824, early in 1827, Van Buren privately made the argument to Richie for an exclusive national convention of Republicans to ensure Jackson's nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] However, it did not immediately come to fruition while state conventions and legislatures took up Jackson as their presidential candidate for the election of 1828 with Vice President John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Such a type of national convention would occur after the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun soon became politically estranged from President Jackson, due in part to an 1830 letter written by Crawford stating that Calhoun, as Secretary of War under President James Monroe, pushed for a reprimand of then-General Jackson for his actions in the 1818 invasion of Florida.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Petticoat affair in which Calhoun's wife, Floride, was a central figure further alienated Jackson from the vice president and his supporters.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The final blow to the relationship came in January 1832, when Calhoun, as President of the Senate, sank Van Buren's nomination as Minister to Great Britain by casting a tie-breaking vote in the United States Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Calhoun was replaced as the party's 1832 vice presidential nominee by Van Buren.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Later that year, on December 28, he resigned as vice president, after having been elected to the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] There he continued to be a proponent of the doctrine of nullification in opposition to Jackson.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The proposal for the convention began with members of Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet", his coterie of informal advisers and confidants.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Major William Berkeley Lewis wrote on May 25, 1831, to Amos Kendall, who was then in New Hampshire.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] He proposed that the New Hampshire legislature call for a national gathering of Republican supporters of the Jackson administration to nominate a candidate for the vice presidency, and asked Kendall to pass the idea to Isaac Hill.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention was called to order by Frederick A.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from all states except Missouri were present.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Governor Robert Lucas of Ohio served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Peter Vivian Daniel, James Fenner, John M.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barclay, and Augustin Smith Clayton were chosen as convention vice presidents.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] John Adams Dix was appointed secretary at the first meeting, with other additional secretaries thereafter.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] A resolution was passed by the convention requiring two-thirds majority support of the delegates for a nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] An address by the Republican delegates of New York gave a history of previous national political activity in the United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] They denounced the National Republicans as Federalists under a new designation and they denounced the Nullifiers while they declared that their own party held the middle ground between the positions of the other two.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The address described what they claimed were political similarities between Andrew Jackson and Thomas Jefferson and it defended the policies of Jackson's administration.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] It characterized Van Buren as a strict constructionist and welcomed his nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention concluded by adopting a resolution calling for an address or report from the delegations to their constituents.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Jackson was nominated via a resolution passed by the convention, affirming the nominations which Jackson had previously received from multiple state legislatures.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot after receiving 208 votes of the 283 cast, 19 more than the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:andrew-johnson/1832-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren defeated their main competitors, Henry Clay and John Sergeant of the National Republican Party, by a large electoral vote margin in the election of 1832.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] The **1835 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 20 to May 22, 1835, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated incumbent Vice President Martin Van Buren for president and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Former Speaker of the House Andrew Stevenson served as the convention chairman.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] With the support of President Andrew Jackson, Van Buren won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson narrowly won the two-thirds majority necessary for the vice presidential nomination, overcoming a challenge from William Cabell Rives of Virginia.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Van Buren and Johnson went on to win the 1836 presidential election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] On February 23, 1835, President Andrew Jackson wrote to James Gwin of Tennessee and claimed a preference for someone who would "most likely to be the choice of the great body of republicans" in regard to his successor.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] He expressed the desire to hold another national convention to nominate candidates for the presidency and vice presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] He instructed Gwin to show the letter to the editor of the *Nashville Republican*.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] The newspaper later reprinted the letter.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Stevenson of Virginia served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Six convention vice presidents and four secretaries were appointed.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Tennessee, Illinois, South Carolina, and Alabama sent no delegates to the convention.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] President Jackson had long planned for Vice President Martin Van Buren to succeed him, and Van Buren was the unanimous choice of the delegates for the presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Jackson and other major Democrats had settled on Richard Mentor Johnson, a Kentucky representative who had fought in the War of 1812, as Van Buren's running mate, but many Virginia Democrats backed William Cabell Rives, the former Ambassador to France.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] A man from Tennessee, Edward Rucker, who was present at the convention but was not sent as a delegate, cast all 15 votes Tennessee was entitled to for Van Buren, and for Johnson for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was nominated for vice president after winning one vote more than the two-thirds majority required.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] The delegation of Virginia declared that it had no confidence in Johnson's character and principles, and would not support him.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Letters went out on May 23 from the convention president and vice presidents asking for the acceptance of the nominations by the nominees.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren replied and accepted the nomination on May 29; Johnson, likewise on June 9.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Whigs did not put forward a national ticket nominated by national convention.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren defeated his many competitors for the presidency in the general election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] While the electors of Virginia supported Van Buren for the presidency, they cast their vice presidential votes for William Smith.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Johnson received a plurality, but not a majority, of the electoral votes for the vice presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1835-democratic-national-convention] In the subsequent contingent election in the Senate, Johnson was elected vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] The **1840 Democratic National Convention** was held in Baltimore, Maryland, from May 5 to May 6.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic Party re-nominated President Martin Van Buren by acclamation, but failed to select a nominee for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren is the only major party presidential nominee since the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Dragged down by the unpopularity of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was defeated by the Whig Party's ticket in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from 21 of 26 states were in attendance.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] States not in attendance were Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, South Carolina and Virginia.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] The 1840 convention was the first at which the party adopted a platform.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates reaffirmed their belief that the Constitution was the primary guide for each state's political affairs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] To them, this meant that all roles of the federal government not specifically defined fell to each respective state government, including such responsibilities as debt created by local projects.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Decentralized power and states' rights pervaded each and every resolution adopted at the convention, including those on slavery, taxes, and the possibility of a central bank.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was not retained on the ticket, as he was largely seen as a liability in the 1836 election and had focused much of his time as vice president on his own economic affairs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Former president Andrew Jackson backed James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk for the position of vice president, but Van Buren supported his vice president's renomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Prior to the convention, several prominent Democrats sought the vice presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Among them were Polk; Senator William R.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] King of Alabama; and Secretary of State John Forsyth of Georgia.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] The convention ultimately failed to nominate a running mate for Van Buren.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren remains the only major party presidential nominee since the passage of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Johnson would both receive electoral votes for vice president in the general election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 30 to December 2, 1840.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the shadow of an incomplete economic recovery from the Panic of 1837, Whig nominee William Henry Harrison defeated incumbent President Martin Van Buren of the Democratic Party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the first of two Whig victories in presidential elections, but was the only one where they won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the third rematch in American history.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In 1839, the Whigs held a national convention for the first time.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1839 Whig National Convention saw 1836 nominee William Henry Harrison defeat former Secretary of State Henry Clay and General Winfield Scott.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren faced little opposition at the 1840 Democratic National Convention, but controversial Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson was not renominated.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats thus became the only major party since 1800 to fail to select a vice presidential nominee.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Referencing vice presidential nominee John Tyler and Harrison's participation in the Battle of Tippecanoe, the Whigs campaigned on the slogan of "Tippecanoe and Tyler Too." With Van Buren weakened by economic woes, Harrison won a popular majority and 234 of 294 electoral votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Voter participation surged as white male suffrage became nearly universal, and a contemporary record of 42.4% of the voting age population voted for Harrison.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren's loss made him the third president to lose re-election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs did not enjoy the benefits of victory.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 67-year-old Harrison, the oldest U.S. president elected until Ronald Reagan won the 1980 election, died a little more than a month after inauguration.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was succeeded by John Tyler, who unexpectedly proved not to be a Whig.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] While Tyler had been a staunch supporter of Clay at the convention, he was a former Democrat, a passionate supporter of states' rights, and effectively an independent.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] As President, Tyler blocked the Whigs' legislative agenda and was expelled from the Whig Party, subsequently the second independent (after Washington) to serve as president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren would be the last incumbent president to lose his reelection bid in a general election until fellow Democrat Grover Cleveland in 1888.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time a challenger to an incumbent president got a majority of the vote until 1932.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time as of 2024 where the incumbent president seeking re-election flipped a state yet failed to secure re-election, with Van Buren winning South Carolina, despite losing it four years earlier, and losing re-election to Harrison.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The first national convention of the Whig Party was called for by members of the party in Congress and it was attended by almost 250 delegates in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, William Henry Harrison, and Winfield Scott ran for the party's presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegations of each state balloted separately before meeting together with the other representatives of the states.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Clay initially led on the first ballot, but Harrison won on the final ballot with 148 votes compared to Clay's 90 votes and Scott's 16 votes after supporters from Scott switched to Harrison.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] John Tyler was selected as a factional and geographical balance to Harrison.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic members of the New Hampshire General Court made a call for the 1840 Democratic National Convention which was held in Baltimore, Maryland in May 1840.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from twenty-two states attended the convention, but the sizes of the delegations varied with New Jersey having fifty-nine delegates to cast its eight votes while Massachusetts only had one delegate to cast its fourteen votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] A committee was formed to make recommendations for the nominations and the committee supported Van Buren for renomination which was approved by acclamation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, the vice-presidential nomination was left vacant due to opposition to Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson's personal life.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After the negative views of Freemasonry among a large segment of the public began to wane in the mid-1830s, the Anti-Masonic Party disintegrated.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Many leaders began to move to the Whig party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Remaining leaders met in September 1837 in Washington, and agreed to maintain the party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The third Anti-Masonic Party National Convention was held in Philadelphia on November 13–14, 1838.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] By this time, the party had been almost entirely supplanted by the Whigs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates unanimously voted to nominate William Henry Harrison for president (who the party had supported for president the previous election along with Francis Granger for vice president) and Daniel Webster for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, when the Whig National Convention nominated Harrison with John Tyler as his running mate, the Anti-Masonic Party did not make an alternate nomination and ceased to function and was fully absorbed into the Whigs by 1840.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, Myron Holley, Joshua Leavitt, and Gerrit Smith proposed the creation of an anti-slavery party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In July 1839, two resolutions proposed by Holley at the American Anti-Slavery Society's meeting in Cleveland, called for the creation of an abolitionist party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nevertheless, the supporters nominated Birney and Francis Julius LeMoyne as a presidential ticket at a meeting in Warsaw, New York.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, Birney declined the presidential nomination as he preferred a nomination to be made by a regular body of abolitionists and LeMoyne also declined the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Smith and Holley made a call for an abolitionist nominating convention to be held on April 1, 1840, in Albany, New York.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 121 delegates attended the delegation and selected a presidential ticket of Birney and Thomas Earle. which was accepted.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney was unable to campaign during the election as he was in England until November.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party received opposition from followers of William Lloyd Garrison and abolitionist Whigs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the wake of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was widely unpopular, and Harrison, following Andrew Jackson's strategy, ran as a war hero and man of the people while presenting Van Buren as a wealthy snob living in luxury at the public expense.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Although Harrison was comfortably wealthy and well educated, his "log cabin" image caught fire, sweeping all sections of the country.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison avoided campaigning on the issues, with his Whig Party attracting a broad coalition with few common ideals.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig strategy overall was to win the election by avoiding discussion of difficult national issues such as slavery or the national bank and concentrate instead on exploiting dissatisfaction over the failed policies of the Van Buren administration with colorful campaigning techniques.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was the first president to campaign actively for office.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] He did so with the slogan "Tippecanoe and Tyler too".
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Tippecanoe referred to Harrison's military victory over a group of Shawnee Native Americans at a river in Indiana called Tippecanoe in 1811.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] For their part, Democrats laughed at Harrison for being too old for the presidency, and referred to him as "Granny", hinting that he was senile.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs took advantage of this quip and declared that Harrison was "the log cabin and hard cider candidate", a man of the common people from the rough-and-tumble West.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] They depicted Harrison's opponent, President Martin Van Buren, as a wealthy snob who was out of touch with the people.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, it was Harrison who came from a family of wealthy planters, while Van Buren's father was a tavernkeeper.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison however moved to the frontier and for years lived in a log cabin, while Van Buren had been a well-paid government official.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, the election was held in the wake of the Panic of 1837, one of the worst economic depressions in the nation's history, and voters blamed Van Buren, seeing him as unsympathetic to struggling citizens.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 31.9% of the voting age population and 80.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time that a majority of southern voters participated in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison won the support of western settlers and eastern bankers alike.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,179 counties/independent cities making returns, Harrison won in 699 (59.29%) while Van Buren carried 477 (40.46%).
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Three counties (0.25%) in the South split evenly between Harrison and Van Buren.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The extent of Van Buren's unpopularity was evident in Harrison's victories in New York, the president's home state, and in Tennessee, where Andrew Jackson himself had come out of retirement to stump for his former vice-president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time a Democratic president lost re-election, as well as the first of only two times (the other being 1980) that a Democratic president lost re-election and lost the popular vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the first election in U.S. history in which a candidate won more than a million popular votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election where Indiana voted for the Whigs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election where the Whigs won Maine, Michigan, and Mississippi.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in American history in which a majority of voters in Alabama and a majority of voters in Mississippi voted for different candidates.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1840 presidential election was the only time in which four people who either had been or would become a U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] President (Van Buren, Harrison, Tyler, and Polk) received at least one vote in the Electoral College when it voted for president and vice-president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison's victory won him precious little time as chief executive of the United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After giving the longest inauguration speech in U.S. history (lasting about 1 hour and 45 minutes, in cold weather and rain), Harrison served only one month as president before dying of pneumonia on April 4, 1841.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–257.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the 1997 film *Amistad*, Van Buren (played by Nigel Hawthorne) is seen campaigning for re-election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1840-united-states-presidential-election] These scenes have been criticized for their historical inaccuracy.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The **1844 Democratic National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held in Baltimore, Maryland from May 27 through 30.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated former Governor James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk of Tennessee for president and former Senator George M.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Dallas of Pennsylvania for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The convention included three former vice presidents who sought the presidential nomination, John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun, Van Buren and Richard Mentor Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Though his opposition to the annexation of Texas cost him support with expansionists and Southerners, former President Martin Van Buren entered the convention with the backing of a majority of the delegates.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Before presidential balloting commenced, the convention voted to reinstate a rule requiring the presidential nominee to win two-thirds of the vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the first presidential ballot, Van Buren won a majority, but fell short of a two-thirds requirement.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] As the balloting continued, Van Buren continually lost support to Johnson, former Governor Lewis Cass of Michigan, and Senator James Buchanan of Pennsylvania.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Though he had entered the convention hoping to be nominated for vice president, Polk had the strong support of former President Andrew Jackson and was acceptable to the different factions of the party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] He won the nomination on the ninth presidential ballot, thus becoming the first dark horse candidate to win a major party's presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] After Senator Silas Wright of New York declined the vice presidential nomination, the convention selected Dallas as Polk's running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket went on to win the 1844 presidential election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] At the outset of the convention, the leading contender was former President Martin Van Buren of New York, who had been defeated in the 1840 election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] His principal opponent was Lewis Cass of Michigan, who had served as United States Secretary of War under President Andrew Jackson.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The annexation of Texas was a major issue.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren publicly opposed immediate annexation because it might lead to a sectional crisis over the status of slavery in the West.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] This position cost Van Buren the support of Southern and expansionist Democrats, but he believed that backing annexation would cost him the support of his fellow New Yorkers and other Northeasterners.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren's supporters arrived at the convention with a majority of the delegates pledged to support him on the first ballot.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Cass, meanwhile, had support from a handful of Southern states, but far fewer delegates pledged to him.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] At the previous convention, in 1840, a majority of votes had been sufficient to secure the nomination, but this had been a departure from the party's previous rule requiring a two-thirds majority.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Early in the proceedings, Senator Robert J.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Walker of Mississippi, in cooperation with Senator (and future president) James Buchanan of Pennsylvania called for reinstatement of the 1832 and 1835 convention rule requiring the nominee to win two-thirds of the votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Following a historical pattern in which a minority faction of Northern Democrats delivered votes to produce southern wing victories for pro-slavery legislation, the Van Burenite delegates split over the pivotal vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Fully one-third of the pro-Van Buren delegates (52 of 154) voted to reinstate the two-thirds rule, along with 90 of 104 anti-Van Buren delegates, producing a final vote of 148 to 116.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The rule would remain in place until the 1936 Democratic National Convention, when it was revoked by supporters of Franklin D.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren supporters persisted in spite of the two-thirds rule setback, garnering 146 votes for their candidate on the first ballot, a 55% simple majority, but short of the now required 177 votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Middle and Deep South pro-annexationists opposed Van Buren 75 to 3, depriving northern anti-annexationists the 31 votes needed for victory.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Support for Van Buren dwindled in subsequent ballots from 146 to 99, at which point Van Burenites were reduced to blocking nominations of numerous candidates, among them James Buchanan, Lewis Cass of Michigan, John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun, and Levi Woodbury of New Hampshire.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Incumbent President John Tyler, a former Democrat who was elected to the vice presidency on the 1840 Whig Party ticket, also hoped to win the support of delegates, but he was unable to find any backers.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Southern intransigence had succeeded in eliminating Van Buren and his stand on Texas annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] If the Democratic Party was to avoid dissolution at a national level, an acceptable nominee, fully committed to immediate annexation would be required, yet capable of unifying the party in the general election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren was open to deferring to Senator Silas Wright of New York, but Wright was a major supporter of Van Buren for president and had already declined to be considered.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the eighth ballot, the historian George Bancroft, a delegate from Massachusetts, proposed former Speaker of the House of Representatives James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk, who had also served as Governor of Tennessee, had entered the convention in hopes of becoming the vice presidential nominee.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] However, former President Andrew Jackson, who remained popular in the party, believed Polk was just the man to head the Democratic ticket.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Although a slaveholder himself, Polk never enunciated a slavery expansionist position with respect to Texas annexation, as had John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Southern Democrats benefited from the Tyler-Calhoun machinations in eliminating Martin Van Buren as a presidential candidate, and clearing the way for the pro-annexation nationalist Polk.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the ninth ballot, Van Buren instructed his delegates to support Polk, beginning a stampede to Polk that ended with him winning the nomination unanimously.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Polk became the first dark horse, or little-known, presidential nominee.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren complied with his party's decision to unite under a pro-annexation candidate, and worked to win New York state for Polk.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Despite Whig efforts to cast Polk as an unknown – "Who is James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk?" they asked rhetorically – he was respected as an effective political operator.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] As a national imperialist, he exhibited an unwavering support for Manifest Destiny, perceived as a non-sectional devotion to expansionism, whether slave-soil Texas or free-soil Oregon Territory.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk argued that Texas and Oregon had always belonged to the United States by right.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] He called for "the immediate reannexation of Texas" and for the "reoccupation" of the disputed Oregon territory.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk's political reputation was expected to diffuse northern Democratic resentment towards the Slavepower, while delivering Texas to the Deep South.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Richard Mentor Johnson had both campaigned for the vice presidency prior to the convention, but with Polk's nomination for president, the party looked to the northern states for a running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Wright refused to reconsider despite Democratic Party attempts to convince him to do so.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] On the second ballot, John Fairfield attracted significant support, but this was not even close to the 184 votes required for nomination: on the third ballot, the convention settled on George M.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Dallas, a conservative from Pennsylvania.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] The basic events of the convention are outlined in the song "James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-democratic-national-convention] Polk" by the rock band They Might Be Giants.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk narrowly defeated Whig nominee Henry Clay in a close contest turning on the controversial issues of slavery and the annexation of the Republic of Texas.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in which both major party nominees served as Speaker of the House at one point, and the first in which neither candidate held elective office at the time.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] President John Tyler's pursuit of Texas annexation divided both major parties.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Annexation would geographically expand American slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It also risked war with Mexico while the United States engaged in sensitive possession and boundary negotiations with Great Britain, which controlled Canada, over Oregon.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Texas annexation thus posed both domestic and foreign policy risks.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties had wings in the North and the South, but the possibility of the expansion of slavery threatened a sectional split in each party.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Expelled by the Whig Party after vetoing key Whig legislation and lacking a firm political base, Tyler hoped to use the annexation of Texas to win the presidency as an independent or at least to have decisive, pro-Texas influence over the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The initial frontrunner for the Democratic nomination was former President Martin Van Buren, but his opposition to the annexation of Texas damaged his candidacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition from former President Andrew Jackson and most Southern delegations, plus a nomination rule change specifically aimed to block him, prevented Van Buren from winning the necessary two-thirds vote of delegates to the 1844 Democratic National Convention.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk, former Governor of Tennessee and Speaker.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He was the first successful dark horse for the presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk ran on a platform embracing popular commitment to expansion, often referred to as Manifest Destiny.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler dropped out of the race and endorsed Polk.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs nominated Henry Clay, a famous, long-time party leader who was the early favorite but who conspicuously waffled on Texas annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Though a Southerner from Kentucky and a slave owner, Clay chose to focus on the risks of annexation while claiming not to oppose it personally.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His awkward, repeated attempts to adjust and finesse his position on Texas confused and alienated voters, contrasting negatively with Polk's consistent clarity.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk successfully linked the dispute with Britain over Oregon with the Texas issue.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic nominee thus united anti-slavery Northern expansionists, who demanded Oregon, with pro-slavery Southern expansionists who demanded Texas.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the national popular vote, Polk beat Clay by fewer than 40,000 votes, a margin of 1.4%.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney of the anti-slavery Liberty Party won 2.3% of the vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College winner was decided by New York where Polk won by just over 5,100 votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Had Clay won the state, he would have won the presidency with 141 electoral votes to Polk's 134.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney's vote share in New York exceeded Polk's margin of victory over Clay, marking the first time a third party candidate vote share exceeded the margin of a winning candidate in a decisive state. of a United States presidential election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After Polk's victory, Tyler annexed Texas, which was the proximate cause of the Mexican–American War during Polk's presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs and Democrats embarked upon their campaigns during the climax of the congressional gag rule controversies in 1844, which prompted Southern congressmen to suppress northern petitions to end the slave trade in the District of Columbia.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-annexation petitions to Congress sent from northern anti-slavery forces, including state legislatures, were similarly suppressed.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Intra-party sectional compromises and maneuvering on slavery politics during these divisive debates placed significant strain on the northern and southern wings that comprised each political organization.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The question as to whether the institution of slavery and its aristocratic principles of social authority were compatible with democratic republicanism was becoming "a permanent issue in national politics".
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In 1836, a portion of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas declared its independence to form the Republic of Texas.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Texans, mostly American immigrants from the Deep South, many of whom owned slaves, sought to bring their republic into the Union as a state.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] At first, the subject of annexing Texas to the United States was shunned by both major American political parties.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Although they recognized Texas sovereignty, Presidents Andrew Jackson (1829–1837) and Martin Van Buren (1837–1841) declined to pursue annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of bringing another slave state into the Union was fraught with problems.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties – the Democrats and Whigs – viewed Texas statehood as something "not worth a foreign war [with Mexico]" or the "sectional combat" that annexation would provoke in the United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The incumbent President John Tyler, formerly vice-president, had assumed the presidency upon the death of William Henry Harrison in 1841.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler, a Whig in name only, emerged as a states' rights advocate committed to slavery expansion in defiance of Whig principles.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After he vetoed the Whig domestic legislative agenda, he was expelled from his own party on September 13, 1841.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Politically isolated, but unencumbered by party restraints, Tyler aligned himself with a small faction of Texas annexationists in a bid for election to a full term in 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler became convinced that Great Britain was encouraging a Texas–Mexico rapprochement that might lead to slave emancipation in the Texas republic.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Accordingly, he directed Secretary of State Abel P.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Upshur of Virginia to initiate, then relentlessly pursue, secret annexation talks with Texas minister to the United States Isaac Van Zandt, beginning on October 16, 1843.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler submitted his Texas-U.S. treaty for annexation to the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Senate, delivered April 22, 1844, where a two-thirds majority was required for ratification.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The newly appointed Secretary of State John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun of South Carolina (assuming his post March 29, 1844) included a document known as the Packenham Letter with the Tyler bill that was calculated to inject a sense of crisis in Southern Democrats of the Deep South.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In it, he characterized slavery as a social blessing and the acquisition of Texas as an emergency measure necessary to safeguard the "peculiar institution" in the United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Tyler and Calhoun sought to unite the South in a crusade that would present the North with an ultimatum: support Texas annexation or lose the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Whigs considered Texas annexation particularly egregious, since Mexico had outlawed slavery in Coahuila y Tejas in 1829, before Texas independence had been declared.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 1844 presidential campaigns evolved within the context of this struggle over Texas annexation, which was tied to the question of slavery expansion and national security.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] All candidates in the 1844 presidential election had to declare a position on this explosive issue.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Martin Van Buren, President of the United States between 1837 and 1841, and chief architect of Jacksonian democracy, was the presumptive Democratic presidential contender in the spring of 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun withdrawing his bid for the presidency in January 1844, the campaign was expected to focus on domestic issues.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren regarded the Tyler annexation measure as an attempt to sabotage his bid for the White House by exacerbating the already strained North-South Democratic alliance regarding slavery expansion.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation of Texas was the chief political issue of the day.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, initially the leading candidate, opposed immediate annexation because it might lead to a sectional crisis over the status of slavery in the West and lead to war with Mexico.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This position cost Van Buren the support of southern and expansionist Democrats; as a result, he failed to win the nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates likewise could not settle on Lewis Cass, the former Secretary of War, whose credentials also included past service as a U.S. minister to France.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On the eighth ballot, the historian George Bancroft, a delegate from Massachusetts, proposed former House Speaker James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He called for "the immediate re-annexation of Texas" and for the "re-occupation" of the disputed Oregon territory.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On the next roll call, the convention unanimously accepted Polk, who became the first dark horse, or little-known, presidential candidate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates selected Senator Silas Wright of New York for Vice President, but Wright, an admirer of Van Buren, declined the nomination to become the second person to decline a vice presidential nomination.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren realized that accommodating slavery expansionists in the South would open the Northern Democrats to charges of appeasement to the Slave power from the strongly anti-annexation Northern Whigs and some Democrats.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He crafted an emphatically anti-Texas position that temporized with expansionist southern Democrats, laying out a highly conditional scenario that delayed Texas annexation indefinitely.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the Hammett letter, published April 27, 1844 (penned April 20), he counseled his party to reject Texas under a Tyler administration.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, annexation of Texas as a territory would proceed, tentatively, under a Van Buren administration, only when the American public had been consulted on the matter and Mexico's cooperation had been pursued to avoid an unnecessary war.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A military option might be advanced if a groundswell of popular support arose for Texas, certified with a congressional mandate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In these respects, Martin Van Buren differed from Henry Clay, who would never tolerate annexation without Mexico's assent.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] With the publication of Clay's Raleigh Letter and Van Buren's Hammett letter, Van Burenite Democrats hoped that their candidate's posture on Texas would leave southern pro-annexationists with exactly one choice for president: Martin Van Buren.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In this, they misjudged the political situation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler and the southern pro-annexationists posed a potentially far greater threat than Clay, in that the Tyler-Calhoun treaty would put immense pressure on the northern Democrats to comply with southern Democrats' demands for Texas.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Hammett letter utterly failed to reassure Middle and Deep South extremists who had responded favorably to Calhoun's Pakenham Letter.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A minority of the southern Democrat leadership remained obdurate that Northern Democratic legislators would ignore their constituents' opposition to slavery expansion and unite in support of Texas annexation once exposed to sufficient southern pressure.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Former President Andrew Jackson publicly announced his support for immediate Texas annexation in May 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had facilitated Tyler's Texas negotiations in February 1844 by reassuring Sam Houston, the President of Texas, that the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As the Senate debated the Tyler treaty, Jackson declared that the popular support among Texans for annexation should be respected, and any delay would result in a British dominated Texas Republic that would promote slave emancipation and pose a foreign military threat to the southwest United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The former military hero went further, urging all Jacksonian Democrats to block Martin Van Buren from the party ticket and seek a Democratic presidential candidate fully committed to the immediate annexation of Texas.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Jackson abandoned the traditional Jeffersonian-Jacksonian formula that had required its Northern and Southern wings to compromise on constitutional slavery disputes.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Texas issue was fracturing Van Buren's support among Democrats and would derail his candidacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk furthermore pledged to serve only one term as president.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He would keep this promise, and would die less than three months after leaving office.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation treaty needed a two-thirds vote and was easily defeated in the Senate, largely along partisan lines, 16 to 35 – a two-thirds majority against passage – on June 8, 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs voted 27–1 against the treaty: all northern Whig senators voted nay, and fourteen of fifteen southern Whig senators had joined them.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats voted for the treaty 15–8, with a slight majority of Northern Democrats opposing.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Democrats affirmed the treaty 10–1, with only one slave state senator, Thomas Hart Benton, voting against.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Three days later, Tyler and his supporters in Congress began exploring means to bypass the supermajority requirement for Senate treaty approval.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Substituting the constitutional protocols for admitting regions of the United States into the Union as states, Tyler proposed that alternative, yet constitutional, means be used to bring the Republic of Texas – a foreign country – into the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler and Calhoun, formerly staunch supporters of minority safeguards based on the supermajority requirements for national legislation, now altered their position to facilitate passage of the Tyler treaty.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler's attempt to evade the Senate vote launched a spirited congressional debate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay of Kentucky, effectively the leader of the Whig Party since its inception in 1834, was selected as its nominee at the party's convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on May 1, 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay, a slaveholder, presided over a party in which its Southern wing was sufficiently committed to the national platform to put partisan loyalties above slavery expansionist proposals that might undermine its north–south alliance.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs felt confident that Clay could duplicate Harrison's landslide victory of 1840 against any opposition candidate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Whigs feared that the acquisition of the fertile lands in Texas would produce a huge market for slave labor, inflating the price of slaves and deflating land values in their home states.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Whigs feared that Texas statehood would initiate the opening of a vast "Empire for Slavery".
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Two weeks before the Whig convention in Baltimore, in reaction to Calhoun's Packenham Letter, Clay issued a document known as the Raleigh Letter (issued April 17, 1844) that presented his views on Texas to his fellow southern Whigs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In it, he flatly denounced the Tyler annexation bill and predicted that its passage would provoke a war with Mexico, whose government had never recognized Texas independence.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay underlined his position, warning that even with Mexico's consent, he would block annexation in the event that substantial sectional opposition existed anywhere in the United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig party leadership was acutely aware that any proslavery legislation advanced by its southern wing would alienate its anti-slavery northern wing and cripple the party in the general election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In order to preserve their party, Whigs would need to stand squarely against acquiring a new slave state.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As such, Whigs were content to restrict their 1844 campaign platform to less divisive issues such as internal improvements and national finance.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs picked Theodore Frelinghuysen of New Jersey – "the Christian Statesman" – as Clay's running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] An advocate of the colonization of emancipated slaves, he was acceptable to southern Whigs as an opponent of the abolitionists.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His pious reputation balanced Clay's image as a slave-holding, hard-drinking duelist.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On July 27, 1844, Clay released a position statement, the so-called "Alabama Letter." In it, he counseled his Whig constituency to regard Texas annexation and statehood as merely a short phase in the decline of slavery in the United States, rather than a long term advance for the Slave Power.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay qualified his stance on Texas annexation, declaring "no personal objection to the annexation" of the republic.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He would move back to his original orientation in September 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Whigs expressed outrage at any détente with the Slave Power and accused him of equivocating on Texas annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's central position, however, had not altered: no annexation without northern acquiescence.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's commitment brought Southern Whigs under extreme pressure in their home states and congressional districts, threatening to tarnish their credentials as supporters of slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After the closed session Senate debates on the Tyler-Texas treaty were leaked to the public on April 27, 1844, President Tyler's only hope of success in influencing passage of his treaty was to intervene directly as a spoiler candidate in the 1844 election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His "Democratic-Republican Party", a recycling of the name of Jefferson's party, held its convention on May 27, 1844, in Baltimore, Maryland, a short distance from the unfolding Democratic Party convention that would select James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler was nominated the same day without challenge, accepting the honor on May 30, 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Tyler delegates did not designate a vice-presidential running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk was faced with the possibility that a Tyler ticket might shift votes away from the Democrats and provide Clay with the margin of victory in a close race.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler made clear in his nomination acceptance speech that his overriding concern was the ratification of his Texas annexation treaty.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, he hinted that he would drop out of the race once that end was assured, informing Polk, through Senator Robert J.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Walker of Mississippi, that his campaign efforts were simply a vehicle to mobilize support for Texas annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler concentrated his resources in the states of New York, Pennsylvania and New Jersey, all highly contested states in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Securing enough Democratic support, his withdrawal might prove indispensable to Polk.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk was receptive as long as Tyler could withdraw without raising suspicion of a secret bargain.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] To solidify Tyler's cooperation, Polk enlisted Andrew Jackson to reassure Tyler that Texas annexation would be consummated under a Polk administration.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On August 20, 1844, Tyler dropped out of the presidential race, and Tylerites moved quickly to support the Democratic Party nominee.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party held its 1843 national convention on August 30 in Buffalo, New York, with 148 delegates from twelve states in attendance.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, the party's presidential nominee in the 1840 election, was renominated with 108 votes on the first ballot (Thomas Morris and William Jay received 2 and 1 votes respectively).
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Morris would go on to be nominated for vice-president with 83 votes compared to Gerrit Smith's 22 and Alvan Stewart's 1.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The party received 2.3% of the popular vote in the election, which was the highest it ever received.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Joseph Smith, the mayor of Nauvoo, Illinois, and founder of the Latter-day Saint movement, ran as an independent under the newly created Reform Party with Sidney Rigdon as his running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His top aide Brigham Young campaigned for Smith saying, "He it is that God of Heaven designs to save this nation from destruction and preserve the Constitution." The campaign ended when he was attacked and killed by a mob while in the Carthage, Illinois, jail on June 27, 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] 30.6% of the voting age population and 79% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk's adoption of Manifest Destiny paid dividends at the polls.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] No longer identified with the Tyler-Calhoun "southern crusade for slavery", the western Democrats could embrace Texas annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats enjoyed a huge upsurge in voter turnout, up to 20% over the figures from 1840, especially in the Northwest and Mid-Atlantic regions.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats won Michigan, Illinois, and Indiana and nearly took Ohio, where the concept of Manifest Destiny was most admired.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the Deep South, Clay lost every state to Polk, a huge reversal from the 1840 race, but carried most of the Middle and Border South.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's "waffling" on Texas may have cost him the 41 electoral votes of New York and Michigan.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The former slaveholder, now abolitionist, James Birney of the Liberty Party, received 15,812 and 3,632 votes, respectively, based on his unwavering stand against Texas annexation.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Celebratory shots rang out in Washington on November 7 as returns came in from western New York which clinched the state and the presidency for Polk.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk won by a mere 5,106 out of 470,062 cast in New York, and only 3,422 out of 52,096 votes in Michigan.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Had enough of these voting blocks cast their ballots for the anti-annexationist Clay in New York, he would have defeated Polk.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Still, Clay's opposition to annexation and western slavery expansion served him well among Northern Whigs and nearly secured him the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Clay was the third of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Thomas Jefferson, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay and Bryan are the only two candidates to lose the presidency three times.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This is the most recent presidential election where the election took place on different days in different states.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It is the only presidential election in which both major party nominees were former Speakers of the House.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which Ohio voted for the Whigs.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only presidential election in which the winner, Polk, lost both his birth state of North Carolina and his state of residence, Tennessee, (which he lost by only 123 votes) before Donald Trump's victory in the 2016 presidential election.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of four times that a victorious candidate lost their home state followed by 1916, 1968, and 2016.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk's election confirmed that Manifest Destiny had majority support in the electorate despite Whig opposition.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation of Texas was formalized on March 1, 1845, days before Polk took office.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Mexico refused to accept the annexation and the Mexican–American War broke out in 1846.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Instead of demanding all of Oregon, Polk compromised.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Washington and London negotiated the Buchanan–Pakenham Treaty, which split up the Oregon Territory between the two countries.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Upon the conclusion of the election, Whig publications were disheartened at Henry Clay's loss against Polk's alleged fraud.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Almanac, a yearly collection of political statistics and events of interest to the party, contained in 1845 a column alleging fraud in Louisiana.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It noted that, in one Louisiana parish, Plaquemines, the vote tally exploded from a 240 to 40 vote victory for the Van Buren ticket in 1840 to a 1007 to 37 vote victory for the Polk ticket in 1844.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 970 vote margin was greater than Polk's margin statewide.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 1,007 votes received by Polk exceeded the total number of all white males in the parish in 1840, despite Louisiana having a property requirement to vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A steward, pilot, and passenger of the steamboat *Agnes* reportedly said that the ship ferried voters from New Orleans to Plaquemines parish where the steward was pushed by the Captain to vote for the Polk ticket three times, despite not being of voting age.
[src:andrew-johnson/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A man named Charles Bruland was seen driven out of the voting booth wounded and bloody after attempting to cast a vote for the Clay ticket in Plaquemines Parish.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was born into poverty and never attended school.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was apprenticed as a tailor and worked in several frontier towns before settling in Greeneville, Tennessee, serving as an alderman and mayor before being elected to the Tennessee House of Representatives in 1835.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] After briefly serving in the Tennessee Senate, Johnson was elected to the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] House of Representatives in 1843, where he served five two-year terms.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was the governor of Tennessee for four years, and was elected by the legislature to the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] During his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill, which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In February 1861, Slave states in the Southern U.S., including Tennessee, seceded to form the Confederate States of America, but Johnson remained firmly with the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was the only senator from a Confederate state who did not promptly resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as Military Governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was a logical choice as Lincoln's running mate in 1864 because Lincoln wanted to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Following their victory, Johnson became vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson implemented his own form of Presidential Reconstruction, a series of proclamations directing the seceded states to hold conventions and elections to reform their civil governments.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Southern states returned many of their old leaders and passed Black Codes to deprive the freedmen of many civil liberties, but Congressional Republicans refused to seat legislators from those states and advanced legislation to overrule the Southern actions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson vetoed their bills, and Congressional Republicans overrode him, setting a pattern for the remainder of his presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson opposed the Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Constitution, which gave citizenship to former slaves.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1866, he went on an unprecedented national tour promoting his executive policies, seeking to break Republican opposition.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] As the conflict grew between the branches of government, Congress passed the Tenure of Office Act (1867), restricting Johnson's ability to fire Cabinet officials.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He persisted in trying to dismiss the Secretary of War, Edwin Stanton, but ended up being impeached by the House of Representatives and narrowly avoided conviction in the Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He did not win the 1868 Democratic presidential nomination and left office the following year.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson returned to Tennessee after his presidency and gained some vindication when he was elected to the Senate in 1875, making him the only former president to serve in the Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's strong opposition to federally guaranteed rights for African Americans is widely criticized, and historians have consistently ranked him as one of the worst U.S. presidents.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew Johnson was born in Raleigh, North Carolina, on December 29, 1808, to Jacob Johnson and Mary ("Polly") McDonough, a laundress.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was of English, Scots-Irish, and Scottish ancestry.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He had a brother, William, four years his senior, and an older sister Elizabeth, who died in childhood.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's birth in a two-room shack was a political asset in the mid-19th century, and he frequently reminded voters of his humble origins.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Jacob Johnson was a poor man, as had been his father, William Johnson, but he became town constable of Raleigh before marrying and starting a family.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Jacob Johnson had been a porter for the State Bank of North Carolina, appointed by William Polk, a relative of President James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Both Jacob and Mary were illiterate, and had worked as tavern servants, while Johnson never attended school and grew up in poverty.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Jacob died of an apparent heart attack while ringing the town bell, shortly after rescuing three drowning men, when his son Andrew was three.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Polly Johnson worked as a washerwoman and became the sole support of her family.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Her occupation was then looked down on, as it often took her into other homes unaccompanied.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Since Andrew did not resemble either of his siblings, there are rumors that he may have been fathered by another man.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Polly Johnson eventually remarried to a man named Turner Doughtry, who was as poor as she was.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's mother apprenticed her son William to a tailor, James Selby.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew also became an apprentice in Selby's shop at age ten and was legally bound to serve until his 21st birthday.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson lived with his mother for part of his service, and one of Selby's employees taught him rudimentary literacy skills.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] His education was augmented by citizens who would come to Selby's shop to read to the tailors as they worked.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Even before he became an apprentice, Johnson came to listen.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The readings instilled in him a lifelong love of learning, and his biographer Annette Gordon-Reed suggests that Johnson, later a gifted public speaker, learned the art as he threaded needles and cut cloth.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was unhappy at James Selby's, and after about five years, he and his brother ran away.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Selby responded by placing a reward for their return: "Ten Dollars Reward.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Fearing he would be arrested and returned to Raleigh, Johnson moved to Laurens, South Carolina.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He found work quickly, met his first love, Mary Wood, and made her a quilt as a gift.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] However, she rejected his marriage proposal.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He returned to Raleigh, hoping to buy out his apprenticeship, but could not come to terms with Selby.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Unable to stay in Raleigh, where he risked being apprehended for abandoning Selby, he decided to move west.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson left North Carolina for Tennessee, traveling mostly on foot.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] After a brief period in Knoxville, he moved to Mooresville, Alabama.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He then worked as a tailor in Columbia, Tennessee, but was called back to Raleigh by his mother and stepfather, who saw limited opportunities there and who wished to emigrate west.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson and his party traveled through the Blue Ridge Mountains to Greeneville, Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew Johnson fell in love with the town at first sight, and when he became prosperous purchased the land where he had first camped and planted a tree in commemoration.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In Greeneville, Johnson established a successful tailoring business in the front of his home.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1827, at the age of 18, he married 16-year-old Eliza McCardle, the daughter of a local shoemaker.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The pair were married by Justice of the Peace Mordecai Lincoln, first cousin of Thomas Lincoln, whose son would become president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Johnsons were married for almost 50 years and had five children: Martha (1828), Charles (1830), Mary (1832), Robert (1834), and Andrew Jr.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Though she had tuberculosis, Eliza supported her husband's endeavors.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] She taught him mathematics skills and tutored him to improve his writing.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Shy and retiring by nature, Eliza Johnson usually remained in Greeneville during Johnson's political rise.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] She was not often seen during her husband's presidency; their daughter Martha usually served as official hostess.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's tailoring business prospered during the early years of the marriage, enabling him to hire help and giving him the funds to invest profitably in real estate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He later boasted of his talents as a tailor, "my work never ripped or gave way".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Books about famous orators aroused his interest in political dialogue, and he had private debates on the issues of the day with customers who held opposing views.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He also took part in debates at Greeneville College.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1843, Johnson purchased his first slave, Dolly, who was 14 years old at the time.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Dolly had three children—Liz, Florence and William.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Soon after his purchase of Dolly, he purchased Dolly's half-brother Sam.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Sam Johnson and his wife Margaret had nine children.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Sam became a commissioner of the Freedmen's Bureau and was known for being a proud man who negotiated the nature of his work with the Johnson family.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Notably, he received some monetary compensation for his labors and negotiated with Andrew Johnson to receive a tract of land which Johnson gave him for free in 1867.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1857, Johnson purchased Henry, who was 13 at the time and would later accompany the Johnson family to the White House.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Ultimately, Johnson owned at least ten slaves.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Andrew Johnson freed his slaves on August 8, 1863; they remained with him as paid servants.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] A year later, Johnson, as military governor of Tennessee, proclaimed the freedom of Tennessee's slaves.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Sam and Margaret, Johnson's former slaves, lived in his tailor shop while he was president, without rent.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] As a sign of appreciation for proclaiming freedom, Andrew Johnson was given a watch by newly emancipated people in Tennessee inscribed with "for his Untiring Energy in the Cause of Freedom".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson helped organize a Mechanics' (Working Men's) ticket in the 1829 Greeneville municipal election.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was elected town alderman, along with his friends Blackston McDannel and Mordecai Lincoln.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Following Nat Turner's Rebellion in 1831, a state convention was called to pass a new constitution, including provisions to disenfranchise free people of color.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The convention also wanted to reform real estate tax rates, and provide ways of funding improvements to Tennessee's infrastructure.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The constitution was submitted for a public vote, and Johnson spoke widely for its adoption; the successful campaign provided him with statewide exposure.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] On January 4, 1834, his fellow aldermen elected him mayor of Greeneville.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1835, Johnson made a bid for election to the "floater" (open) seat which Greene County shared with neighboring Washington County in the Tennessee House of Representatives.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Trefousse, Johnson "demolished" the opposition in debate and won the election with a near-two-to-one margin.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] During his Greeneville days, Johnson joined the Tennessee Militia as a member of the 90th Regiment.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He attained the rank of colonel, though while an enrolled member, Johnson was fined for an unknown offense.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Afterwards, he was often addressed or referred to by his rank.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In his first term in the legislature, which met in the state capital of Nashville, Johnson did not consistently vote with either the Democratic or the newly formed Whig Party, though he revered President Andrew Jackson, a Democrat and fellow Tennessean.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The major parties were still determining their core values and policy proposals, with the party system in a state of flux.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] After Brookins Campbell and the Whigs defeated Johnson for reelection in 1837, Johnson would not lose another race for thirty years.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1839, he sought to regain his seat, initially as a Whig, but when another candidate sought the Whig nomination, he ran as a Democrat and was elected.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] From that time he supported the Democratic party and built a powerful political machine in Greene County.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson became a strong advocate for the Democratic Party.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was noted for his oratory in an era when public speaking both informed and entertained the public; people flocked to hear him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1840, Johnson was selected as a presidential elector for Tennessee, giving him more statewide publicity.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Democratic President Martin Van Buren was defeated by former Ohio senator William Henry Harrison, Johnson was instrumental in keeping Greene County in the Democratic column.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was elected to the Tennessee Senate in 1841, where he served a two-year term.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He had achieved financial success in his tailoring business, but sold it to concentrate on politics.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He had also acquired additional real estate, including a larger home and a farm (where his mother and stepfather took residence), and among his assets numbered eight or nine slaves.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Having served in both houses of the state legislature, Johnson saw election to Congress as the next step in his political career.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He engaged in a number of political maneuvers to gain Democratic support, including the displacement of the Whig postmaster in Greeneville, and defeated Jonesborough lawyer John A.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In Washington, he joined a new Democratic majority in the House of Representatives.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson advocated for the interests of the poor, maintained an anti-abolitionist stance, argued for only limited spending by the government and opposed protective tariffs.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] With Eliza remaining in Greeneville, Congressman Johnson shunned social functions in favor of study in the Library of Congress.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although a fellow Tennessee Democrat, James K.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Polk, was elected president in 1844, and Johnson had campaigned for him, the two men had difficult relations, and President Polk refused some of his patronage suggestions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson believed, as did many Southern Democrats, that the Constitution protected private property, including slaves, and thus prohibited the federal and state governments from abolishing slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He won a second term in 1845 against William G.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Brownlow, presenting himself as the defender of the poor against the aristocracy.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In his second term, Johnson supported the Polk administration's decision to fight the Mexican War, seen by some Northerners as an attempt to gain territory to expand slavery westward, and opposed the Wilmot Proviso, a proposal to ban slavery in any territory gained from Mexico.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He introduced for the first time his Homestead Bill, to grant 160 acres (65 ha) to people willing to settle the land and gain title to it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] This issue was especially important to Johnson because of his own humble beginnings.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In the presidential election of 1848, the Democrats split over the slavery issue, and abolitionists formed the Free Soil Party, with former president Van Buren as their nominee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson supported the Democratic candidate, former Michigan senator Lewis Cass.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] With the party split, Whig nominee General Zachary Taylor was easily victorious, and carried Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, due to national interest in new railroad construction and in response to the need for better transportation in his own district, also supported government assistance for the East Tennessee and Virginia Railroad.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] During his campaign for a fourth term, Johnson concentrated on three issues: slavery, homesteads and judicial elections.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Taylor, in August 1849, with a greater margin of victory than in previous campaigns.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] When the House convened in December, the party division caused by the Free Soil Party precluded the formation of the majority needed to elect a Speaker.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson proposed adoption of a rule allowing election of a Speaker by a plurality; some weeks later others took up a similar proposal, and Democrat Howell Cobb was elected.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Once the Speaker election had concluded and Congress was ready to conduct legislative business, the issue of slavery took center stage.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Northerners sought to admit California, a free state, to the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Kentucky's Henry Clay introduced in the Senate a series of resolutions, the Compromise of 1850, to admit California and pass legislation sought by each side.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson voted for all the provisions except for the abolition of the slave trade in the nation's capital.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He pressed resolutions for constitutional amendments to provide for popular election of senators (then elected by state legislatures) and of the president (chosen by the Electoral College), and limiting the tenure of federal judges to 12 years.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] A group of Democrats nominated Landon Carter Haynes to oppose Johnson as he sought a fifth term; the Whigs were so pleased with the internecine battle among the Democrats in the general election that they did not nominate a candidate of their own.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The campaign included fierce debates: Johnson's main issue was the passage of the Homestead Bill; Haynes contended it would facilitate abolition.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson won the election by more than 1,600 votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Though he was not enamored of the party's presidential nominee in 1852, former New Hampshire senator Franklin Pierce, Johnson campaigned for him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Pierce was elected, but he failed to carry Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1852, Johnson managed to get the House to pass his Homestead Bill, but it failed in the Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Whigs had gained control of the Tennessee legislature, and, under the leadership of Gustavus Henry, redrew the boundaries of Johnson's First District to make it a safe seat for their party.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] During this period, Johnson became a Freemason, initiated into Greenville Lodge No.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] If Johnson considered retiring from politics upon deciding not to seek reelection, he soon changed his mind.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] His political friends began to maneuver to get him the nomination for governor.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Democratic convention unanimously named him, though some party members were not happy at his selection.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Whigs had won the past two gubernatorial elections, and still controlled the legislature.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] That party nominated Henry, making the "Henry-mandering" of the First District an immediate issue.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The two men debated in county seats the length of Tennessee before the meetings were called off two weeks before the August 1853 election due to illness in Henry's family.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson won the election by 63,413 votes to 61,163; some votes for him were cast in return for his promise to support Whig Nathaniel Taylor for his old seat in Congress.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Tennessee's governor had little power: Johnson could propose legislation but not veto it, and most appointments were made by the Whig-controlled legislature.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Nevertheless, the office was a "bully pulpit" that allowed him to publicize himself and his political views.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He succeeded in getting the appointments he wanted in return for his endorsement of John Bell, a Whig, for one of the state's U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In his first biennial speech, Johnson urged simplification of the state judicial system, abolition of the Bank of Tennessee, and establishment of an agency to provide uniformity in weights and measures; the last was passed.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was critical of the Tennessee common school system and suggested funding be increased via taxes, either statewide or county by county—a mixture of the two was passed.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Reforms carried out during Johnson's time as governor included the foundation of the State's public library (making books available to all) and its first public school system, and the initiation of regular state fairs to benefit craftsmen and farmers.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although the Whig Party was on its final decline nationally, it remained strong in Tennessee, and the outlook for Democrats there in 1855 was poor.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Feeling that reelection as governor was necessary to give him a chance at the higher offices he sought, Johnson agreed to make the run.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] A series of more than a dozen vitriolic debates ensued.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The issues in the campaign were slavery, the prohibition of alcohol, and the nativist positions of the Know Nothing Party.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson favored the first, but opposed the others.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Gentry was more equivocal on the alcohol question, and had gained the support of the Know Nothings, a group Johnson portrayed as a secret society.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was unexpectedly victorious, albeit with a narrower margin than in 1853.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] When the presidential election of 1856 approached, Johnson hoped to be nominated; some Tennessee county conventions designated him a "favorite son".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] His position that the best interests of the Union were served by slavery in some areas made him a practical compromise candidate for president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He was never a major contender; the nomination fell to former Pennsylvania senator James Buchanan.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Though he was not impressed by either, Johnson campaigned for Buchanan and his running mate, John C.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson decided not to seek a third term as governor, with an eye towards election to the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1857, while returning from Washington, his train derailed, causing serious damage to his right arm.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] This injury would trouble him in the years to come.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The victors in the 1857 state legislative campaign would, once they convened in October, elect a United States Senator.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Campbell wrote to his uncle, "The great anxiety of the Whigs is to elect a majority in the legislature so as to defeat Andrew Johnson for senator.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Should the Democrats have the majority, he will certainly be their choice, and there is no man living to whom the Americans and Whigs have as much antipathy as Johnson." The governor spoke widely in the campaign, and his party won the gubernatorial race and control of the legislature.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's final address as governor gave him the chance to influence his electors, and he made proposals popular among Democrats.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Two days later the legislature elected him to the Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The opposition was appalled, with the Richmond *Whig* newspaper referring to him as "the vilest radical and most unscrupulous demagogue in the Union".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson gained high office due to his proven record as a man popular among the small farmers and self-employed tradesmen who made up much of Tennessee's electorate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He called them the "plebeians"; he was less popular among the planters and lawyers who led the state Democratic Party, but none could match him as a vote-getter.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Mostly denied the party's machinery, he relied on a network of friends, advisers, and contacts.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] One friend, Hugh Douglas, stated in a letter to him, "you have been in the way of our would be great men for a long time.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] At heart many of us never wanted you to be Governor only none of the rest of us Could have been elected at the time and we only wanted to use you.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The new senator took his seat when Congress convened in December 1857 (the term of his predecessor, James C.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He came to Washington as usual without his wife and family; Eliza would visit Washington only once during Johnson's first time as senator, in 1860.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson immediately set about introducing the Homestead Bill in the Senate, but as most senators who supported it were Northern (many associated with the newly founded Republican Party), the matter became caught up in suspicions over the slavery issue.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Southern senators felt that those who took advantage of the provisions of the Homestead Bill were more likely to be Northern non-slaveholders.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The issue of slavery had been complicated by the Supreme Court's ruling earlier in the year in *Dred Scott v.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Sandford* that slavery could not be prohibited in the territories.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, a slaveholding senator from a Southern state, made a major speech in the Senate the following May in an attempt to convince his colleagues that the Homestead Bill and slavery were not incompatible.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Nevertheless, Southern opposition was key to defeating the legislation, 30–22.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1859, it failed on a procedural vote when Vice President Breckinridge broke a tie against the bill, and in 1860, a watered-down version passed both houses, only to be vetoed by Buchanan at the urging of Southerners.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson continued his opposition to spending, chairing a committee to control it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He argued against funding to build infrastructure in Washington, D.C., stating that it was unfair to expect state citizens to pay for the city's streets, even if it was the seat of government.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He opposed spending money for troops to put down the revolt by the Mormons in Utah Territory, arguing for temporary volunteers as the United States should not have a standing army.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In October 1859, abolitionist John Brown and sympathizers raided the federal arsenal at Harpers Ferry, Virginia (today West Virginia).
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Tensions in Washington between pro- and anti-slavery forces increased greatly.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson gave a major speech in the Senate in December, decrying Northerners who would endanger the Union by seeking to outlaw slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Tennessee senator stated that "all men are created equal" from the Declaration of Independence did not apply to African Americans, since the Constitution of Illinois contained that phrase—and that document barred voting by African Americans.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, by this time, was a wealthy man who owned 14 slaves.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson hoped that he would be a compromise candidate for the presidential nomination as the Democratic Party tore itself apart over the slavery question.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Busy with the Homestead Bill during the 1860 Democratic National Convention in Charleston, South Carolina, he sent two of his sons and his chief political adviser to represent his interests in the backroom deal-making.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The convention deadlocked, with no candidate able to gain the required two-thirds vote, but the sides were too far apart to consider Johnson as a compromise.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The party split, with Northerners backing Illinois Senator Stephen Douglas while Southerners, including Johnson, supported Vice President Breckinridge for president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] With former Tennessee senator John Bell running a fourth-party candidacy and further dividing the vote, the Republican Party elected its first president, former Illinois representative Abraham Lincoln.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The election of Lincoln, known to be against the spread of slavery, was unacceptable to many in the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although secession from the Union had not been an issue in the campaign, talk of it began in the Southern states.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson took to the Senate floor after the election, giving a speech well received in the North, "I will not give up this government ...
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Gordon-Reed points out that while Johnson's belief in an indissoluble Union was sincere, he had alienated Southern leaders, including Davis, who would soon be the president of the Confederate States of America, formed by the seceding states.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] If the Tennessean had backed the Confederacy, he would have had small influence in its government.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson returned home when his state took up the issue of secession.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Harris, and the legislature organized a referendum on whether to have a constitutional convention to authorize secession; when that failed, they put the question of leaving the Union to a popular vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Despite threats on Johnson's life, and actual assaults, he campaigned against both questions, sometimes speaking with a gun on the lectern before him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Johnson's eastern region of Tennessee was largely against secession, the second referendum passed, and in June 1861, Tennessee joined the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Believing he would be killed if he stayed, Johnson fled through the Cumberland Gap, where his party was in fact shot at.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He left his wife and family in Greeneville.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] As the only member from a seceded state to remain in the Senate and the most prominent Southern Unionist, Johnson had Lincoln's ear in the early months of the war.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] With most of Tennessee in Confederate hands, Johnson spent congressional recesses in Kentucky and Ohio, trying in vain to convince any Union commander who would listen to conduct an operation into East Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson's first tenure in the Senate came to a conclusion in March 1862 when Lincoln appointed him military governor of Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Much of the central and western portions of that seceded state had been recovered.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although some argued that civil government should simply resume once the Confederates were defeated in an area, Lincoln chose to use his power as commander in chief to appoint military governors over Union-controlled Southern regions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Senate quickly confirmed Johnson's nomination along with the rank of brigadier general.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In response, the Confederates confiscated his land and his slaves, and turned his home into a military hospital.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Later in 1862, after his departure from the Senate and in the absence of most Southern legislators, the Homestead Bill was finally enacted.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Along with legislation for land-grant colleges and for the transcontinental railroad, the Homestead Bill has been credited with opening the Western United States to settlement.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] As military governor, Johnson sought to eliminate rebel influence in the state.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He demanded loyalty oaths from public officials, and shut down all newspapers owned by Confederate sympathizers.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Much of eastern Tennessee remained in Confederate hands, and the ebb and flow of war during 1862 sometimes brought Confederate control again close to Nashville.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] However, the Confederates allowed his wife and family to pass through the lines to join him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson undertook the defense of Nashville as well as he could, though the city was continually harassed by cavalry raids led by General Nathan Bedford Forrest.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Relief from Union regulars did not come until General William S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Rosecrans defeated the Confederates at Murfreesboro in early 1863.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Much of eastern Tennessee was captured later that year.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] When Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863, declaring freedom for all slaves in Confederate-held areas, he exempted Tennessee at Johnson's request.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The proclamation increased the debate over what should become of the slaves after the war, as not all Unionists supported abolition.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson finally decided that slavery had to end.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He wrote, "If the institution of slavery ... seeks to overthrow it [the Government], then the Government has a clear right to destroy it".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He reluctantly supported efforts to enlist former slaves into the Union army, feeling that African-Americans should perform menial tasks to release white Americans to do the fighting.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Nevertheless, he oversaw the recruitment of 20,000 black men into the United States Colored Troops.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In 1860, Lincoln's running mate had been Senator Hannibal Hamlin of Maine.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Hamlin had served competently, was in good health, and was willing to run again, Johnson emerged as running mate for Lincoln's reelection bid in 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln considered several War Democrats for the ticket in 1864, and sent an agent to sound out General Benjamin Butler as a possible running mate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In May 1864, the president dispatched General Daniel Sickles to Nashville on a fact-finding mission.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although Sickles denied that he was there either to investigate or interview the military governor, Johnson biographer Hans L.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Trefousse believes that Sickles's trip was connected to Johnson's subsequent nomination for vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] According to historian Albert Castel in his account of Johnson's presidency, Lincoln was impressed by Johnson's administration of Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Dickinson, a War Democrat, as Seward would probably have had to yield his place if another New Yorker became vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson, once he was told by reporters the likely purpose of Sickles' visit, was active on his own behalf, delivering speeches and having his political friends work behind the scenes to boost his candidacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] To sound a theme of unity in 1864, Lincoln ran under the banner of the National Union Party, rather than that of the Republicans.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] At the party's convention in Baltimore in June, Lincoln was easily nominated, although there had been some talk of replacing him with a cabinet officer or one of the more successful generals.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] After the convention backed Lincoln, former Secretary of War Simon Cameron offered a resolution to nominate Hamlin, but it was defeated.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was nominated for vice president by C.M.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Allen of Indiana with an Iowa delegate seconding it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] On the first ballot, Johnson led with 200 votes to 150 for Hamlin and 108 for Dickinson.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] On the second ballot, Kentucky switched its vote for Johnson, beginning a stampede.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Johnson was named on the second ballot with 491 votes to Hamlin's 17 and eight for Dickinson; the nomination was made unanimous.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln expressed pleasure at the result, "Andy Johnson, I think, is a good man." When word reached Nashville, a crowd assembled and the military governor obliged with a speech contending his selection as a Southerner meant that the rebel states had not actually left the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Although it was unusual at the time for a national candidate to actively campaign, Johnson gave a number of speeches in Tennessee, Kentucky, Ohio, and Indiana.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He also sought to boost his chances in Tennessee while reestablishing civil government by making the loyalty oath even more restrictive, in that voters would now have to swear that they opposed making a settlement with the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] The Democratic candidate for president, George McClellan, hoped to avoid additional bloodshed by negotiation, and so the stricter loyalty oath effectively disenfranchised his supporters.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln declined to override Johnson, and their ticket took the state by 25,000 votes.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Congress refused to count Tennessee's electoral votes, but Lincoln and Johnson did not need them, having won in most states that had voted, and easily secured the election.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Now Vice President-elect, Johnson was eager to complete the work of reestablishing civilian government in Tennessee, although the timetable for the election of a new governor did not allow it to take place until after Inauguration Day, March 4.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] He hoped to remain in Nashville to complete his task, but was told by Lincoln's advisers that he could not stay, but would be sworn in with Lincoln.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In these months, Union troops finished the retaking of eastern Tennessee, including Greeneville.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Just before his departure, the voters of Tennessee ratified a new constitution, which abolished slavery, on February 22, 1865.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] One of Johnson's final acts as military governor was to certify the results.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] On the evening of March 3, Johnson attended a party in his honor at which he drank heavily.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Hung over the following morning at the Capitol, he asked Vice President Hamlin for some whiskey.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Hamlin produced a bottle, and Johnson took two stiff drinks, stating "I need all the strength for the occasion I can have." In the Senate Chamber, Johnson delivered a rambling address as Lincoln, the Congress, and dignitaries looked on.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Almost incoherent at times, he finally meandered to a halt, whereupon Hamlin hastily swore him in as vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Lincoln, who had watched sadly during the debacle, then went to his own swearing-in outside the Capitol, and delivered his acclaimed Second Inaugural Address.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] In the weeks after the inauguration, Johnson only presided over the Senate briefly, and hid from public ridicule at the Maryland home of a friend, Francis Preston Blair.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] When he did return to Washington, it was with the intent of leaving for Tennessee to reestablish his family in Greeneville.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Instead, he remained after word came that General Ulysses S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p01] Grant had captured the Confederate capital of Richmond, Virginia, presaging the end of the war.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On the afternoon of April 14, 1865, Lincoln and Johnson met for the first time since the inauguration.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Trefousse states that Johnson wanted to "induce Lincoln not to be too lenient with traitors"; Gordon-Reed agrees.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] That night, President Lincoln was shot and mortally wounded at Ford's Theatre by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The shooting of the President was part of a conspiracy to assassinate Lincoln, Johnson, and Seward the same night.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward barely survived his wounds, while Johnson escaped attack as his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, got drunk instead of killing the vice president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Farwell, a fellow boarder at the Kirkwood House, awoke Johnson with news of Lincoln's shooting.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson rushed to the President's deathbed, where he remained a short time, on his return promising, "They shall suffer for this.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] They shall suffer for this." Lincoln died at 7:22 the next morning; Johnson's swearing-in occurred between 10 and 11 am with Chief Justice Salmon P.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Chase presiding in the presence of most of the Cabinet.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's demeanor was described by the newspapers as "solemn and dignified".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Some Cabinet members had last seen Johnson, apparently drunk, at the inauguration.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] At noon, Johnson conducted his first Cabinet meeting in the Treasury Secretary's office, and asked all members to remain in their positions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The events of the assassination resulted in speculation, then and subsequently, concerning Johnson and what the conspirators might have intended for him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In the vain hope of having his life spared after his capture, Atzerodt spoke much about the conspiracy, but did not say anything to indicate that the plotted assassination of Johnson was merely a ruse.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Conspiracy theorists point to the fact that on the day of the assassination, Booth came to the Kirkwood House and left one of his cards with Johnson's private secretary, William A.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The message on it was: "Don't wish to disturb you.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson presided with dignity over Lincoln's funeral ceremonies in Washington, before his predecessor's body was sent home to Springfield, Illinois, for interment.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Shortly after Lincoln's death, Union General William T.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Sherman reported he had, without consulting Washington, reached an armistice agreement with Confederate General Joseph E.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnston for the surrender of Confederate forces in North Carolina in exchange for the existing state government remaining in power, with private property rights (slaves) to be respected.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] This did not even grant freedom to those in slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] This was not acceptable to Johnson or the Cabinet, who sent word for Sherman to secure the surrender without making political deals, which he did.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Further, Johnson placed a $100,000 bounty (equivalent to $2.1 million in 2025) on Confederate President Davis, then a fugitive, which gave Johnson the reputation of a man who would be tough on the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] More controversially, he permitted the execution of Mary Surratt for her part in Lincoln's assassination.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Surratt was executed with three others, including Atzerodt, on July 7, 1865.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Upon taking office, Johnson faced the question of what to do with the former Confederacy.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress considered this too lenient; its own plan, requiring a majority of voters to take the loyalty oath, passed both houses in 1864, but Lincoln pocket vetoed it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson had three goals in Reconstruction.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He sought a speedy restoration of the states, on the grounds that they had never truly left the Union, and thus should again be recognized once loyal citizens formed a government.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] To Johnson, African-American suffrage was a delay and a distraction; it had always been a state responsibility to decide who should vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Second, political power in the Southern states should pass from the planter class to his beloved "plebeians".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson feared that the freedmen, many of whom were still economically bound to their former masters, might vote at their direction.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's third priority was election in his own right in 1868, a feat no one who had succeeded a deceased president had managed to accomplish, attempting to secure a Democratic anti-Congressional Reconstruction coalition in the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Republicans had formed a number of factions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Radical Republicans sought voting and other civil rights for African Americans.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] They believed that the freedmen could be induced to vote Republican in gratitude for emancipation, and that black votes could keep the Republicans in power and Southern Democrats, including former rebels, out of influence.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] They believed that top Confederates should be punished.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Moderate Republicans sought to keep the Democrats out of power at a national level, and prevent former rebels from resuming power.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] They were not as enthusiastic about the idea of African-American suffrage as their Radical colleagues, either because of their own local political concerns, or because they believed that the freedman would be likely to cast his vote badly.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Northern Democrats favored the unconditional restoration of the Southern states.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] They did not support African-American suffrage, which might threaten Democratic control in the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson was initially left to devise a Reconstruction policy without legislative intervention, as Congress was not due to meet again until December 1865.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Radical Republicans told the President that the Southern states were economically in a state of chaos and urged him to use his leverage to insist on rights for freedmen as a condition of restoration to the Union.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] But Johnson, with the support of other officials including Seward, insisted that the franchise was a state, not a federal matter.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's first Reconstruction actions were two proclamations, with the unanimous backing of his Cabinet, on May 29.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] One recognized the Virginia government led by provisional Governor Francis Pierpont.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The second provided amnesty for all ex-rebels except those holding property valued at $20,000 or more; it also appointed a temporary governor for North Carolina and authorized elections.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Neither of these proclamations included provisions regarding black suffrage or freedmen's rights.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The President ordered constitutional conventions in other former rebel states.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] As Southern states began the process of forming governments, Johnson's policies received considerable public support in the North, which he took as unconditional backing for quick reinstatement of the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] While he received such support from the white South, he underestimated the determination of Northerners to ensure that the war had not been fought for nothing.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] It was important, in Northern public opinion, that the South acknowledge its defeat, that slavery be ended, and that the lot of African Americans be improved.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Voting rights were less important at the time—only a handful of Northern states (mostly in New England) gave African-American men the right to vote on the same basis as whites, and in late 1865, Connecticut, Wisconsin, and Minnesota voted down African-American suffrage proposals by large margins.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Northern public opinion tolerated Johnson's inaction on black suffrage as an experiment, to be allowed if it quickened Southern acceptance of defeat.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Instead, white Southerners felt emboldened.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] A number of Southern states passed Black Codes, binding African-American laborers to farms on annual contracts they could not quit, and allowing law enforcement at whim to arrest them for vagrancy and rent out their labor.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Most Southerners elected to Congress were former Confederates, with the most prominent being Georgia Senator-designate and former Confederate vice president Alexander Stephens.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress assembled in early December 1865; Johnson's conciliatory annual message to them was well received.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Nevertheless, Congress refused to seat the Southern legislators and established a committee to recommend appropriate Reconstruction legislation.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Northerners were outraged at the idea of unrepentant Confederate leaders, such as Stephens, rejoining the federal government at a time when emotional wounds from the war remained raw.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] They saw the Black Codes placing African Americans in a position barely above slavery.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Republicans also feared that restoration of the Southern states would return the Democrats to power.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Stewart in his book on Johnson's impeachment, "the violence and poverty that oppressed the South would galvanize the opposition to Johnson".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress was reluctant to confront the President, and initially only sought to fine-tune Johnson's policies towards the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] By late January 1866, he was convinced that winning a showdown with the Radical Republicans was necessary to his political plans – both for the success of Reconstruction and for reelection in 1868.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He would have preferred that the conflict arise over the legislative efforts to enfranchise African Americans in the District of Columbia, a proposal that had been defeated overwhelmingly in an all-white referendum.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] A bill to accomplish this passed the House of Representatives, but to Johnson's disappointment, stalled in the Senate before he could veto it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Illinois Senator Lyman Trumbull, leader of the Moderate Republicans and Chairman of the Judiciary Committee, was anxious to reach an understanding with the President.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He ushered through Congress a bill extending the Freedmen's Bureau beyond its scheduled abolition in 1867, and the first Civil Rights Bill, to grant citizenship to the freedmen.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Trumbull met several times with Johnson and was convinced the President would sign the measures (Johnson rarely contradicted visitors, often fooling those who met with him into thinking he was in accord).
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In fact, the President opposed both bills as infringements on state sovereignty.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Additionally, both of Trumbull's bills were unpopular among white Southerners, whom Johnson hoped to include in his new party.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson vetoed the Freedman's Bureau bill on February 18, 1866, to the delight of white Southerners and the puzzled anger of Republican legislators.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He considered himself vindicated when a move to override his veto failed in the Senate the following day.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson believed that the Radicals would now be isolated and defeated and that the moderate Republicans would form behind him; he did not understand that Moderates also wanted to see African Americans treated fairly.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On February 22, 1866, Washington's Birthday, Johnson gave an impromptu speech to supporters who had marched to the White House and called for an address in honor of the first president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In his hour-long speech, he instead referred to himself over 200 times.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] More damagingly, he also spoke of "men ... still opposed to the Union" to whom he could not extend the hand of friendship he gave to the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When called upon by the crowd to say who they were, Johnson named Pennsylvania Congressman Thaddeus Stevens, Massachusetts Senator Charles Sumner, and abolitionist Wendell Phillips, and accused them of plotting his assassination.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Republicans viewed the address as a declaration of war, while one Democratic ally estimated Johnson's speech cost the party 200,000 votes in the 1866 congressional midterm elections.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Although strongly urged by moderates to sign the Civil Rights Act of 1866, Johnson broke decisively with them by vetoing it on March 27.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In his veto message, he objected to the measure because it conferred citizenship on the freedmen at a time when 11 out of 36 states were unrepresented in the Congress, and that it "discriminated" in favor of African Americans and against whites.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Within three weeks, Congress had overridden his veto, the first time that had been done on a major bill in American history.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The veto, often seen as a key mistake of Johnson's presidency, convinced moderates there was no hope of working with him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Historian Eric Foner, in his volume on Reconstruction, views it as "the most disastrous miscalculation of his political career".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] According to Stewart, the veto was "for many his defining blunder, setting a tone of perpetual confrontation with Congress that prevailed for the rest of his presidency".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress also proposed the Fourteenth Amendment to the states.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Written by Trumbull and others, it was sent for ratification by state legislatures in a process in which the president plays no part, though Johnson opposed it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The amendment was designed to put the key provisions of the Civil Rights Act into the Constitution, but also went further.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The amendment extended citizenship to every person born in the United States (except Indians on reservations), penalized states that did not give the vote to freedmen, and most importantly, created new federal civil rights that could be protected by federal courts.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] It also guaranteed that the federal debt would be paid and forbade repayment of Confederate war debts.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Further, it disqualified many former Confederates from office, although the disability could be removed — by Congress, not the president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Both houses passed the Freedmen's Bureau Act a second time, and again the President vetoed it; this time, the veto was overridden.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] By the summer of 1866, when Congress finally adjourned, Johnson's method of restoring states to the Union by executive fiat, without safeguards for the freedmen, was in deep trouble.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] His home state of Tennessee ratified the Fourteenth Amendment despite the President's opposition.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When Tennessee did so, Congress immediately seated its proposed delegation, embarrassing Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Efforts to compromise failed, and a political war ensued between the united Republicans on one side, and on the other, Johnson and his Northern and Southern allies in the Democratic Party.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He called a convention of the National Union Party.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Republicans had returned to using their previous identifier; Johnson intended to use the discarded name to unite his supporters and gain election to a full term, in 1868.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The battleground was the election of 1866; Southern states were not allowed to vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson campaigned vigorously, undertaking a public speaking tour, known as the "Swing Around the Circle".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The trip, including speeches in Chicago, St.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Louis, Indianapolis, and Columbus, proved politically disastrous, with the President making controversial comparisons between himself and Jesus, and engaging in arguments with hecklers.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] These exchanges were attacked as beneath the dignity of the presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Republicans won by a landslide, increasing their two-thirds majority in Congress, and made plans to control Reconstruction.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson blamed the Democrats for giving only lukewarm support to the National Union movement.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Even with the Republican victory in November 1866, Johnson considered himself in a strong position.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Fourteenth Amendment had not yet been ratified by enough states to go into force, with Tennessee alone among the Southern or border states in voting for it.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] As the amendment required ratification by three-quarters of the states to become part of the Constitution, he believed the deadlock would be broken in his favor, leading to his election in 1868.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Once it reconvened in December 1866, an energized Congress began passing legislation, often over a presidential veto; this included the District of Columbia voting bill.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Congress admitted Nebraska to the Union over a veto, and the Republicans gained two senators and a state that promptly ratified the amendment.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's veto of a bill for statehood for Colorado Territory was sustained; enough senators agreed that a district with a population of 30,000 was not yet worthy of statehood to win the day.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In January 1867, Congressman Stevens introduced legislation to dissolve the Southern state governments and reconstitute them into five military districts, under martial law.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The states would begin again by holding constitutional conventions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] African Americans could vote for or become delegates; former Confederates could not.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In the legislative process, Congress added to the bill that restoration to the Union would follow the state's ratification of the Fourteenth Amendment, and completion of the process of adding it to the Constitution.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson and the Southerners attempted a compromise, whereby the South would agree to a modified version of the amendment without the disqualification of former Confederates, and for limited black suffrage.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Republicans insisted on the full language of the amendment, and the deal fell through.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Although Johnson could have pocket vetoed the First Reconstruction Act as it was presented to him less than ten days before the end of the Thirty-Ninth Congress, he chose to veto it directly on March 2, 1867; Congress overruled him the same day.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Also on March 2, Congress passed the Tenure of Office Act over the President's veto, in response to statements during the Swing Around the Circle that he planned to fire Cabinet secretaries who did not agree with him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Secretary of War Edwin Stanton was an able and hard-working man, but difficult to deal with.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson both admired and was exasperated by his War Secretary, who, in combination with General of the Army Grant, worked to undermine the president's Southern policy from within his own administration.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson considered firing Stanton, but respected him for his wartime service as secretary.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton, for his part, feared allowing Johnson to appoint his successor and refused to resign, despite his public disagreements with his president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The new Congress met for a few weeks in March 1867, then adjourned, leaving the House Committee on the Judiciary behind, tasked in the first impeachment inquiry against Johnson with reporting back to the full House whether there were grounds for Johnson to be impeached.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] This committee duly met, examined the President's bank accounts, and summoned members of the Cabinet to testify.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When a federal court released former Confederate president Davis on bail on May 13 (he had been captured shortly after the war), the committee investigated whether the President had impeded the prosecution.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] It learned that Johnson was eager to have Davis tried.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] A bipartisan majority of the committee voted down impeachment charges; the committee adjourned on June 3.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Later in June, Johnson and Stanton battled over the question of whether the military officers placed in command of the South could override the civil authorities.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The President had Attorney General Henry Stanbery issue an opinion backing his position that they could not.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson sought to pin down Stanton either as for, and thus endorsing Johnson's position, or against, showing himself to be opposed to his president and the rest of the Cabinet.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton evaded the point in meetings and written communications.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When Congress reconvened in July, it passed a Reconstruction Act against Johnson's position, waited for his veto, overrode it, and went home.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In addition to clarifying the powers of the generals, the legislation also deprived the President of control over the Army in the South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] With Congress in recess until November, Johnson decided to fire Stanton and relieve one of the military commanders, General Philip Sheridan, who had dismissed the governor of Texas and installed a replacement with little popular support.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson was initially deterred by a strong objection from Grant, but on August 5, the President demanded Stanton's resignation; the secretary refused to quit with Congress out of session.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson then suspended him pending the next meeting of Congress as permitted under the Tenure of Office Act; Grant agreed to serve as temporary replacement while continuing to lead the Army.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Grant, under protest, followed Johnson's order transferring Sheridan and another of the district commanders, Daniel Sickles, who had angered Johnson by firmly following Congress's plan.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The President also issued a proclamation pardoning most Confederates, exempting those who held office under the Confederacy, or who had served in federal office before the war but had breached their oaths.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Although Republicans expressed anger with his actions, the 1867 elections generally went Democratic.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] No seats in Congress were directly elected in the polling, but the Democrats took control of the Ohio General Assembly, allowing them to defeat for reelection one of Johnson's strongest opponents, Senator Benjamin Wade.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Voters in Ohio, Connecticut, and Minnesota turned down propositions to grant African Americans the vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The adverse results momentarily put a stop to Republican calls to impeach Johnson, who was elated by the elections.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Nevertheless, once Congress met in November, the Judiciary Committee reversed itself and passed a resolution of impeachment against Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] After much debate about whether anything the President had done was a high crime or misdemeanor, the standard under the Constitution, the resolution was defeated by the House of Representatives on December 7, 1867, by a vote of 57 in favor to 108 opposed.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson notified Congress of Stanton's suspension and Grant's interim appointment.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In January 1868, the Senate disapproved of his action, and reinstated Stanton, contending the President had violated the Tenure of Office Act.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Grant stepped aside over Johnson's objection, causing a complete break between them.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson then dismissed Stanton and appointed Lorenzo Thomas to replace him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton refused to leave his office, and on February 24, 1868, the House impeached the President for intentionally violating the Tenure of Office Act, by a vote of 128 to 47.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The House subsequently adopted eleven articles of impeachment, for the most part alleging that he had violated the Tenure of Office Act, and had questioned the legitimacy of Congress.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On March 5, 1868, the impeachment trial began in the Senate and lasted almost three months; Congressmen George S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Boutwell, Benjamin Butler and Thaddeus Stevens acted as managers for the House, or prosecutors, and William M.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Curtis and former Attorney General Stanbery were Johnson's counsel; Chief Justice Chase served as presiding judge.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The defense relied on the provision of the Tenure of Office Act that made it applicable only to appointees of the current administration.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Since Lincoln had appointed Stanton, the defense maintained Johnson had not violated the act, and also argued that the President had the right to test the constitutionality of an act of Congress.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's counsel insisted that he make no appearance at the trial, nor publicly comment about the proceedings, and except for a pair of interviews in April, he complied.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson maneuvered to gain an acquittal; for example, he pledged to Iowa Senator James W.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Grimes that he would not interfere with Congress's Reconstruction efforts.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Grimes reported to a group of Moderates, many of whom voted for acquittal, that he believed the President would keep his word.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson also promised to install the respected John Schofield as War Secretary.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Ross received assurances that the new, Radical-influenced constitutions ratified in South Carolina and Arkansas would be transmitted to the Congress without delay, an action which would give him and other senators political cover to vote for acquittal.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] One reason senators were reluctant to remove the President was that his successor would have been Ohio Senator Wade, the president *pro tempore* of the Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Wade, a lame duck who left office in early 1869, was a Radical who supported such measures as women's suffrage, placing him beyond the pale politically in much of the nation.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Additionally, a President Wade was seen as an obstacle to Grant's ambitions.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] With the dealmaking, Johnson was confident of the result in advance of the verdict, and in the days leading up to the ballot, newspapers reported that Stevens and his Radicals had given up.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On May 16, the Senate voted on the 11th article of impeachment, accusing Johnson of firing Stanton in violation of the Tenure of Office of Act once the Senate had overturned his suspension.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Thirty-five senators voted "guilty" and 19 "not guilty", thus falling short by a single vote of the two-thirds majority required for conviction under the Constitution.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Ten Republicans—Senators Grimes, Ross, Trumbull, James Dixon, James Rood Doolittle, Daniel Sheldon Norton, William Pitt Fessenden, Joseph S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Van Winkle—voted to acquit the President.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] With Stevens bitterly disappointed at the result, the Senate then adjourned for the Republican National Convention; Grant was nominated for president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The Senate returned on May 26 and voted on the second and third articles, with identical 35–19 results.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Faced with those results, Johnson's opponents gave up and dismissed proceedings.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Stanton "relinquished" his office on May 26, and the Senate subsequently confirmed Schofield.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When Johnson renominated Stanbery to return to his position as attorney general after his service as a defense manager, the Senate refused to confirm him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Allegations were made at the time and again later that bribery dictated the outcome of the trial.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Even when it was in progress, Representative Butler began an investigation, held contentious hearings, and issued a report, unendorsed by any other congressman.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Butler focused on a New York–based "Astor House Group", supposedly led by political boss and editor Thurlow Weed.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] This organization was said to have raised large sums of money from whiskey interests through Cincinnati lawyer Charles Woolley to bribe senators to acquit Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Butler went so far as to imprison Woolley in the Capitol building when he refused to answer questions, but failed to prove bribery.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Soon after taking office as president, Johnson reached an accord with Secretary of State William H.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward that there would be no change in foreign policy.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In practice, this meant that Seward would continue to run things as he had under Lincoln.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward and Lincoln had been rivals for the nomination in 1860; the victor hoped that Seward would succeed him as president in 1869.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] At the time of Johnson's accession, the French had intervened in Mexico, sending troops there.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] While many politicians had indulged in saber rattling over the Mexican matter, Seward preferred quiet diplomacy, warning the French through diplomatic channels that their presence in Mexico was unacceptable.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Although the President preferred a more aggressive approach, Seward persuaded him to follow his lead.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In April 1866, the French government informed Seward that its troops would be brought home in stages, to conclude by November 1867.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On August 14, 1866, Johnson and his cabinet gave a reception for Queen Emma of Hawaii who was returning to Hawaii after her trip to Britain and Europe.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Seward was an expansionist, and sought opportunities to gain territory for the United States.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] After the loss of the Crimean War in the 1850s, the Russian government saw its North American colony (today Alaska) as a financial liability, and feared losing control to Britain whose troops would easily swoop in and annex the territory from neighboring Canada in any future conflict.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Negotiations between Russia and the U.S. over the sale of Alaska were halted due to the outbreak of the Civil War, but after the U.S. victory in the war, talks resumed.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Russia instructed its minister in Washington, Baron Eduard de Stoeckl, to negotiate a sale.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] De Stoeckl did so deftly, getting Seward to raise his offer from $5 million (coincidentally, the minimum that Russia had instructed de Stoeckl to accept) to $7 million, and then getting $200,000 added by raising various objections.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] This sum of $7.2 million is equivalent to $166 million in present-day terms.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On March 30, 1867, de Stoeckl and Seward signed the treaty, working quickly as the Senate was about to adjourn.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson and Seward took the signed document to the President's Room in the Capitol, only to be told there was no time to deal with the matter before adjournment.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The President summoned the Senate into session to meet on April 1; that body approved the treaty, 37–2.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Emboldened by his success in Alaska, Seward sought acquisitions elsewhere.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] His only success was staking an American claim to uninhabited Wake Island in the Pacific, which would be officially claimed by the U.S. in 1898.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He came close with the Danish West Indies as Denmark agreed to sell and the local population approved the transfer in a plebiscite, but the Senate never voted on the treaty and it expired.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Another treaty that fared badly was the Johnson-Clarendon convention, negotiated in settlement of the *Alabama* Claims, for damages to American shipping from British-built Confederate raiders.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Negotiated by the United States Minister to Britain, former Maryland senator Reverdy Johnson, in late 1868, it was ignored by the Senate during the remainder of the President's term.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The treaty was rejected after he left office, and the Grant administration later negotiated considerably better terms from Britain.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson appointed nine Article III federal judges during his presidency, all to United States district courts; he did not appoint a justice to serve on the Supreme Court.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson appointed his Greeneville crony, Samuel Milligan, to the United States Court of Claims, where he served from 1868 until his death in 1874.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In June 1866, Johnson signed the Southern Homestead Act into law, believing that the legislation would assist poor whites.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Around 28,000 land claims were successfully patented, although few former slaves benefitted from the law, fraud was rampant, and much of the best land was off-limits, reserved for grants to veterans or railroads.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In June 1868, Johnson signed an eight-hour law passed by Congress that established an eight-hour workday for laborers and mechanics employed by the Federal Government.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Although Johnson told members of a Workingmen's party delegation in Baltimore that he could not directly commit himself to an eight-hour day, he nevertheless told the same delegation that he greatly favoured the "shortest number of hours consistent with the interests of all".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Selcer, however, the good intentions behind the law were "immediately frustrated" as wages were cut by 20%.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson sought nomination by the 1868 Democratic National Convention in New York in July 1868.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He remained very popular among Southern whites, and boosted that popularity by issuing, just before the convention, a pardon ending the possibility of criminal proceedings against any Confederate not already indicted, meaning that only Davis and a few others still might face trial.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On the first ballot, Johnson was second to former Ohio representative George H.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Pendleton, who had been his Democratic opponent for vice president in 1864.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's support was mostly from the South, and fell away as the ballots passed.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On the 22nd ballot, former New York governor Horatio Seymour was nominated, and the President received only four votes, all from Tennessee.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson sent Congress proposals for amendments to limit the president to a single six-year term and make the president and the Senate directly elected, and for term limits for judges.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When the President was slow to officially report ratifications of the Fourteenth Amendment by the new Southern legislatures, Congress passed a bill, again over his veto, requiring him to do so within ten days of receipt.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He still delayed as much as he could, but was required, in July 1868, to report the ratifications making the amendment part of the Constitution.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Seymour's operatives sought Johnson's support, but he long remained silent on the presidential campaign.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] It was not until October, with the vote already having taken place in some states, that he mentioned Seymour at all, and he never endorsed him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Nevertheless, Johnson regretted Grant's victory, in part because of their animus from the Stanton affair.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In his annual message to Congress in December, Johnson urged the repeal of the Tenure of Office Act and told legislators that had they admitted their Southern colleagues in 1865, all would have been well.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He celebrated his 60th birthday in late December with a party for several hundred children, though not including those of President-elect Grant, who did not allow his to go.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On Christmas Day 1868, Johnson issued a final amnesty, this one covering everyone, including Davis.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He also issued, in his final months in office, pardons for crimes, including one for Dr.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Samuel Mudd, controversially convicted of involvement in the Lincoln assassination (he had set Booth's broken leg) and imprisoned in Fort Jefferson on Florida's Dry Tortugas.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] On March 3, the President hosted a large public reception at the White House on his final full day in office.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Grant had made it known that he was unwilling to ride in the same carriage as Johnson, as was customary, and Johnson refused to go to the inauguration at all.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Despite an effort by Seward to prompt a change of mind, he spent the morning of March 4 finishing last-minute business, and then shortly after noon rode from the White House to the home of a friend.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] After leaving the presidency, Johnson remained for some weeks in Washington, then returned to Greeneville for the first time in eight years.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He was honored with large public celebrations along the way, especially in Tennessee, where cities hostile to him during the war hung out welcome banners.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He had arranged to purchase a large farm near Greeneville to live on after his presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Some expected Johnson to run for Governor of Tennessee or for the Senate again, while others thought that he would become a railroad executive.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson found Greeneville boring, and his private life was embittered by the suicide of his son Robert in 1869.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Seeking vindication for himself, and revenge against his political enemies, he launched a Senate bid soon after returning home.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Tennessee had gone Republican, but court rulings restoring the vote to some whites and suppression of the African-American vote by the Ku Klux Klan led to a Democratic victory in the legislative elections in August 1869.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson was seen as a likely victor in the Senate election, although hated by Radical Republicans, and by some Democrats because of his wartime activities.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Although he was at one point within a single vote of victory in the legislature's balloting, the Republicans eventually elected Henry Cooper over Johnson, 54–51.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In 1872, there was a special election for an at-large congressional seat for Tennessee; Johnson initially sought the Democratic nomination, but when he saw that it would go to former Confederate general Benjamin F.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Cheatham, decided to run as an independent.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The former president was defeated, finishing third, but the split in the Democratic Party defeated Cheatham in favor of an old Johnson Unionist ally, Horace Maynard.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In 1873, Johnson contracted cholera during an epidemic but recovered; that year he lost about $73,000 (~$1.73 million in 2024) when the First National Bank of Washington went under, though he was eventually repaid much of the sum.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He began looking towards the next Senate election to take place in the legislature in early 1875.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson began to woo the farmers' Grange movement; with his Jeffersonian leanings, he easily gained their support.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He spoke throughout the state in his final campaign tour.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Few African Americans outside the large towns were now able to vote as Reconstruction faded in Tennessee, setting a pattern that would be repeated in the other Southern states; the white domination would last almost a century.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In the Tennessee legislative elections in August, the Democrats elected 92 legislators to the Republicans' eight, and Johnson went to Nashville for the legislative session.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] When the balloting for the Senate seat began on January 20, 1875, he led with 30 votes, but did not have the required majority as three former Confederate generals, one former colonel, and a former Democratic congressman split the vote with him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's opponents tried to agree on a single candidate who might gain majority support and defeat him, but failed, and he was elected on January 26 on the 54th ballot, with a margin of a single vote.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's comeback garnered national attention, with the *St.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Louis Republican* calling it "the most magnificent personal triumph which the history of American politics can show".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] At his swearing-in in the Senate on March 5, 1875, he was greeted with flowers, and sworn in alongside Hamlin (his predecessor as vice president) by incumbent Vice President Henry Wilson (who as senator had voted for Johnson's ouster).
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Many Republicans ignored Senator Johnson, though some, such as Ohio's John Sherman (who had voted for conviction), shook his hand.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson remains the only former president to serve in the Senate.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He spoke only once in the short session, on March 22 lambasting President Grant for his use of federal troops in support of Louisiana's Reconstruction government.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The former president asked, "How far off is military despotism?" and concluded his speech, "may God bless this people and God save the Constitution".
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson returned home after the special session concluded.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] In late July 1875, convinced some of his opponents were defaming him in the Ohio gubernatorial race, he decided to travel there to give speeches.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He began the trip on July 28, and broke the journey at his daughter Mary's farm near Elizabethton, where his daughter Martha was also staying.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] That evening he had a stroke, but refused medical treatment until the next day, when he did not improve and two doctors were sent for from Elizabethton.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He seemed to respond to their ministrations, but had another stroke on the evening of July 30, and died early the following morning at the age of 66.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] President Grant had the "painful duty" of announcing the death of the only surviving past president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Northern newspapers, in their obituaries, tended to focus on Johnson's loyalty during the war, while Southern ones paid tribute to his actions as president.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Johnson's funeral was held on August 3 in Greeneville.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] He was buried with his body wrapped in an American flag and a copy of the U.S.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] Constitution placed under his head, according to his wishes.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p02] The burial ground was dedicated as the Andrew Johnson National Cemetery in 1906, and with his home and tailor's shop, is part of the Andrew Johnson National Historic Site.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] According to Castel, "historians [of Johnson's presidency] have tended to concentrate to the exclusion of practically everything else upon his role in that titanic event [Reconstruction]." Through the remainder of the 19th century, there were few historical evaluations of Johnson and his presidency.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Memoirs from Northerners who had dealt with him, such as former vice president Henry Wilson and Maine Senator James G.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Blaine, depicted him as an obstinate boor who tried to favor the South in Reconstruction but was frustrated by Congress.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Beale in his journal article about the historiography of Reconstruction, "Men of the postwar decades were more concerned with justifying their own position than they were with painstaking search for truth.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] The turn of the 20th century saw the first significant historical evaluations of Johnson.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Rhodes ascribed Johnson's faults to his personal weaknesses, and blamed him for the problems of the postbellum South.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Other early 20th-century historians, such as John Burgess, future president Woodrow Wilson, and William Dunning, concurred with Rhodes, believing Johnson flawed and politically inept but concluding that he had tried to carry out Lincoln's plans for the South in good faith.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] The resulting volumes, such as David Miller DeWitt's *The Impeachment and Trial of President Andrew Johnson* (1903), presented him far more favorably than they did those who had sought to oust him.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] In James Schouler's 1913 *History of the Reconstruction Period*, the author accused Rhodes of being "quite unfair to Johnson", though agreeing that the former president had created many of his own problems through inept political moves.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] These works had an effect; although historians continued to view Johnson as having deep flaws which sabotaged his presidency, they saw his Reconstruction policies as fundamentally correct.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] In 1942, Van Heflin portrayed the former president as a fighter for democracy in the Hollywood film *Tennessee Johnson*.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] In 1948, a poll of his colleagues by historian Arthur M.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Schlesinger deemed Johnson among the average presidents; in 1956, one by Clinton L.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Rossiter named him as one of the near-great chief executives.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Earlier historians, including Beale, believed that money drove events, and had seen Reconstruction as an economic struggle.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] They also accepted, for the most part, that reconciliation between North and South should have been the top priority of Reconstruction.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] In the 1950s, historians began to focus on the African-American experience as central to Reconstruction.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] They rejected completely any claim of black inferiority, which had marked many earlier historical works, and saw the developing civil rights movement as a second Reconstruction; some neoabolitionist writers stated they hoped their work on the postbellum era would advance the cause of civil rights.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] These authors sympathized with the Radical Republicans for their desire to help the African American, and saw Johnson as callous towards the freedman.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] In a number of works from 1956 onwards by such historians as Fawn Brodie, the former president was depicted as a successful saboteur of efforts to better the freedman's lot.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] These volumes included major biographies of Stevens and Stanton.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Reconstruction was increasingly seen as a noble effort to integrate the freed slaves into society.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] In the early 21st century, Johnson is among those commonly mentioned as the worst presidents in U.S. history.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] The problems these men had to confront were enormous.
[src:andrew-johnson/andrew-johnson-p03] Trefousse considers Johnson's legacy to be "the maintenance of white supremacy.
